1
00:00:45,793 --> 00:00:50,712
In the 1 960s, my generation
set out on a journey of change.

2
00:00:50,837 --> 00:00:53,478
Coming out of an atmosphere
of conformity,

3
00:00:53,601 --> 00:00:55,797
a new spirit began to appear.

4
00:00:55,923 --> 00:00:58,598
One of the first signs
was a demonstration

5
00:00:58,726 --> 00:01:01,879
organised by Berkeley students
in May of 1 960

6
00:01:02,009 --> 00:01:05,401
against the House
Un-American Activities Committee.

7
00:01:05,533 --> 00:01:09,006
What we are here to do
is to gather information

8
00:01:09,138 --> 00:01:13,499
as we are ordered to do
by an act of congress

9
00:01:13,622 --> 00:01:17,584
with respect to the general operation
of communist conspiracies.

10
00:01:17,706 --> 00:01:21,543
I'm not in the habit of being
intimidated and I won't start now.

11
00:01:21,671 --> 00:01:25,633
- Next question.
- What was your question?

12
00:01:25,755 --> 00:01:28,590
Are you a member
of the Communist Party?

13
00:01:29,199 --> 00:01:30,518
We came out to protest

14
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:34,795
because we were against HUAC's
suppression of political freedom.

15
00:01:34,925 --> 00:01:37,839
In the '50s,
HUAC created a climate of fear

16
00:01:37,969 --> 00:01:41,567
by putting people on trial
for their political beliefs.

17
00:01:41,692 --> 00:01:45,370
Any views left of centre
were labelled subversive.

18
00:01:45,497 --> 00:01:48,012
We refused to go back to McCarthyism.

19
00:01:48,140 --> 00:01:51,613
If you think
that I am going to cooperate

20
00:01:51,743 --> 00:01:56,138
with this collection of Judases,

21
00:01:56,268 --> 00:02:00,663
of men who sit there in violation
of the United States Constitution,

22
00:02:00,793 --> 00:02:05,552
if you think I'll cooperate
with you in any way, you are insane.

23
00:02:05,678 --> 00:02:08,638
As witness after witness
denounced the committee,

24
00:02:08,762 --> 00:02:10,674
the hearings grew stormy.

25
00:02:10,804 --> 00:02:14,196
The halls outside were filled
with students seeking admission.

26
00:02:14,328 --> 00:02:17,208
Suddenly the police
turned fire hoses full force

27
00:02:17,332 --> 00:02:20,007
on the demonstrators
inside the rotunda

28
00:02:20,134 --> 00:02:23,572
and then dragged them down the steps
of City Hall.

29
00:02:24,138 --> 00:02:26,369
It turned out to be
a political baptism

30
00:02:26,501 --> 00:02:30,099
that transformed fear
into determination.

31
00:02:30,946 --> 00:02:35,580
Something had changed.
After this, it would never be the same.

32
00:02:35,711 --> 00:02:37,942
The whole thing might have died down

33
00:02:38,074 --> 00:02:41,626
except for the fact
that the committee made a film.

34
00:02:41,758 --> 00:02:45,036
It was called Operation Abolition.

35
00:02:45,161 --> 00:02:48,918
The film presented all of us...
I had been in these demonstrations.

36
00:02:49,045 --> 00:02:51,800
It presented all of us
as, somehow or other,

37
00:02:51,929 --> 00:02:54,684
engaged in a vast communist plot,

38
00:02:54,812 --> 00:02:58,011
not only to try to overthrow
the US government,

39
00:02:58,135 --> 00:03:01,926
but, worse, to abolish the House
Un-American Activities Committee.

40
00:03:08,307 --> 00:03:11,028
Operation Abolition.

41
00:03:11,149 --> 00:03:14,827
This is what the communists
call their current drive

42
00:03:14,953 --> 00:03:18,915
to destroy the House Committee
on Un-American Activities

43
00:03:19,038 --> 00:03:22,716
and to render sterile
the security laws of our government.

44
00:03:23,323 --> 00:03:28,003
You will see revealed the long-time
classic communist tactic

45
00:03:28,127 --> 00:03:33,684
in which a relatively few
well-trained hard-core communist agents

46
00:03:34,295 --> 00:03:37,414
are able to incite non-communists

47
00:03:37,537 --> 00:03:41,328
to perform the dirty work
of the Communist Party.

48
00:03:41,462 --> 00:03:43,658
That movie was scheduled to be shown

49
00:03:43,785 --> 00:03:46,779
at the Harvard ROTC class.

50
00:03:46,908 --> 00:03:49,663
The ROTC had a class on campus.

51
00:03:49,792 --> 00:03:52,388
They were going to show
Operation Abolition.

52
00:03:52,514 --> 00:03:56,510
I'd heard all about Operation Abolition
and I was opposed to it.

53
00:03:56,639 --> 00:04:00,874
So a bunch of us
decided to go to the class to protest.

54
00:04:01,004 --> 00:04:03,759
I remember very well
the way we protested.

55
00:04:03,886 --> 00:04:08,520
In the film, the students stand up
singing The Star-Spangled Banner

56
00:04:08,651 --> 00:04:13,092
to show HUAC don't pull
you're more American than us on us.

57
00:04:13,217 --> 00:04:17,179
The group of us stood up
in the ROTC class

58
00:04:17,300 --> 00:04:21,741
to show that we're in solidarity
with the students in San Francisco.

59
00:04:31,316 --> 00:04:33,592
But what I really remember clearly

60
00:04:33,718 --> 00:04:37,475
is thinking, ''Wait a minute.
What am I doing here?''

61
00:04:37,603 --> 00:04:39,275
''Why aren't I there?''

62
00:04:40,166 --> 00:04:46,007
And I checked this story out
with people who were at Berkeley

63
00:04:46,132 --> 00:04:48,693
and they told me
the exact same story,

64
00:04:48,815 --> 00:04:52,572
that Operation Abolition
had recruited them to Berkeley,

65
00:04:52,699 --> 00:04:55,898
that they had seen it
round the country

66
00:04:56,022 --> 00:04:58,583
and gone in to see it as a protest

67
00:04:58,705 --> 00:05:02,017
and they'd thought,
''Wow! Let's go there.''

68
00:05:37,347 --> 00:05:39,623
The university's been called upon

69
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:43,188
to educate previously unimagined
numbers of students,

70
00:05:43,314 --> 00:05:46,992
to respond to the expanding claims
of national service,

71
00:05:47,118 --> 00:05:50,670
to merge its activities with industry
as never before.

72
00:05:51,563 --> 00:05:53,839
Characteristic of this transformation

73
00:05:53,965 --> 00:05:56,321
is the growth
of the knowledge industry

74
00:05:56,448 --> 00:06:00,444
which is permeating government
and business and to draw into it

75
00:06:00,573 --> 00:06:04,728
more and more people raised
to higher and higher levels of skill.

76
00:06:04,857 --> 00:06:08,375
The production, distribution
and consumption of knowledge

77
00:06:08,501 --> 00:06:13,978
is said to account for 29 percent
of gross national product.

78
00:06:14,108 --> 00:06:16,225
Knowledge production is growing

79
00:06:16,349 --> 00:06:20,140
at about twice the rate
of the rest of the economy.

80
00:06:20,274 --> 00:06:24,429
What the railroads did for
the second half of the last century

81
00:06:24,559 --> 00:06:27,917
and the automobile
for the first half of this century

82
00:06:28,042 --> 00:06:30,603
may be done for the second half
of this century

83
00:06:30,725 --> 00:06:32,397
by the knowledge industry

84
00:06:32,527 --> 00:06:37,241
and that is to service
the focal point for national growth.

85
00:06:37,373 --> 00:06:41,449
When we went to college, President
Kerr's vision became our reality.

86
00:06:41,577 --> 00:06:44,616
The University of California
was a knowledge factory,

87
00:06:44,740 --> 00:06:47,620
the biggest public university
in America.

88
00:06:47,744 --> 00:06:50,544
It did research
for major corporations

89
00:06:50,667 --> 00:06:53,581
and it ran the government's
nuclear weapons labs.

90
00:06:53,711 --> 00:06:57,468
Of the seven campuses,
Berkeley was the jewel in the crown

91
00:06:57,594 --> 00:06:59,950
with the most prestigious faculty.

92
00:07:00,077 --> 00:07:04,278
Within the sea of students, there was
little evidence of political life.

93
00:07:04,402 --> 00:07:08,444
But a few of us, who were interested
in politics, found each other

94
00:07:08,566 --> 00:07:11,446
and started an organisation
called SLATE.

95
00:07:11,569 --> 00:07:14,324
Some radical students
had gotten together

96
00:07:14,453 --> 00:07:19,577
to run a slate of candidates
in the student elections.

97
00:07:19,699 --> 00:07:23,820
Although SLATE was not solely
about student elections,

98
00:07:23,943 --> 00:07:27,142
the student elections
were used as a kind of platform

99
00:07:27,266 --> 00:07:30,021
through which we could educate
other students

100
00:07:30,150 --> 00:07:33,189
and reach them
about the various issues

101
00:07:33,313 --> 00:07:35,111
that were alive during that time.

102
00:07:35,235 --> 00:07:38,388
Friends wrote me letters
of the discussions happening

103
00:07:38,518 --> 00:07:40,271
in the coffee shops of Berkeley.

104
00:07:40,401 --> 00:07:43,156
People were interested in politics
there.

105
00:07:43,284 --> 00:07:49,399
They'd already organised some little
student activist group on campus

106
00:07:49,530 --> 00:07:52,683
that was starting to experiment
with doing things.

107
00:07:52,814 --> 00:07:56,172
I grew up in a small ethnic community
in Buffalo, New York.

108
00:07:56,298 --> 00:07:58,973
I knew I couldn't live
within its limitations.

109
00:07:59,101 --> 00:08:02,653
I had a couple of years at college.
I quit. I hitchhiked around.

110
00:08:02,785 --> 00:08:05,220
I ended up in San Francisco.
I got married.

111
00:08:05,348 --> 00:08:09,105
Then I went back to school.
I came to Berkeley really...

112
00:08:09,232 --> 00:08:13,513
I was looking for truth.
I was looking for meaning in my life.

113
00:08:13,636 --> 00:08:17,074
One of the most distressing tasks
of a university president

114
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:20,399
is to pretend
that the protest and outrage

115
00:08:20,524 --> 00:08:22,880
of each new generation of undergraduates

116
00:08:23,007 --> 00:08:25,283
is really fresh and meaningful.

117
00:08:25,410 --> 00:08:30,010
In fact, it is one of the most
predictable controversies we know.

118
00:08:30,134 --> 00:08:33,732
The participants go through a ritual
of hackneyed complaints

119
00:08:33,859 --> 00:08:35,851
almost as ancient as academe,

120
00:08:35,981 --> 00:08:38,656
while believing that what is said
is radical and new.

121
00:08:38,784 --> 00:08:41,345
From the beginning,
the administration at Cal

122
00:08:41,466 --> 00:08:47,068
was trying to undermine
and prevent what we were trying to do.

123
00:08:47,193 --> 00:08:49,424
They were very upset

124
00:08:49,556 --> 00:08:53,393
about the introduction
of what they called off-campus issues.

125
00:08:53,519 --> 00:08:55,351
Anything to do with civil rights

126
00:08:55,482 --> 00:08:58,521
or with the testing
of nuclear weapons

127
00:08:58,645 --> 00:09:02,766
or apartheid in South Africa,
these were off-campus issues.

128
00:09:02,890 --> 00:09:07,331
This was what we were attacking.
We were opposed to sandbox politics.

129
00:09:07,454 --> 00:09:10,129
The administration
started turning the screws.

130
00:09:10,258 --> 00:09:12,727
They disenfranchised
the graduate students,

131
00:09:12,861 --> 00:09:15,376
because that was
a big block of the SLATE vote.

132
00:09:15,504 --> 00:09:18,498
Then they threw
the organisation off campus.

133
00:09:18,627 --> 00:09:20,858
There was a big outrage at that.

134
00:09:20,989 --> 00:09:22,308
We got reinstated.

135
00:09:22,431 --> 00:09:26,029
So there was a growing community
of people

136
00:09:26,155 --> 00:09:30,710
who wanted to make
liberal or left or radical,

137
00:09:30,841 --> 00:09:35,282
however they thought about it,
politics legitimate in a country.

138
00:09:37,968 --> 00:09:42,488
When we look at modern man,
we have to face the fact...

139
00:09:43,775 --> 00:09:45,528
..that modern man suffers

140
00:09:45,656 --> 00:09:48,934
from a kind of poverty
of the spirit...

141
00:09:50,621 --> 00:09:55,335
..which stands in glaring contrast

142
00:09:55,467 --> 00:09:58,506
to his scientific and technological
abundance.

143
00:09:58,631 --> 00:10:00,987
We've learned to fly the air
like birds.

144
00:10:01,113 --> 00:10:04,073
We've learned to swim the seas
like fish.

145
00:10:04,196 --> 00:10:08,272
Yet we haven't learned to walk the earth
as brothers and sisters.

146
00:10:21,175 --> 00:10:23,930
More than any other cause,
the civil rights movement

147
00:10:24,058 --> 00:10:26,368
became the wellspring
of student activism

148
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:29,494
and inspired our entire generation.

149
00:10:29,624 --> 00:10:33,302
In 1 963, Berkeley students
began to band together

150
00:10:33,428 --> 00:10:37,709
with black activists to protest
discriminatory hiring practices

151
00:10:37,833 --> 00:10:41,225
of Bay Area businesses.
We sat in at restaurants,

152
00:10:41,356 --> 00:10:44,270
supermarkets
and automobile showrooms.

153
00:10:45,161 --> 00:10:48,235
Our biggest challenge came
when we tried to secure jobs

154
00:10:48,364 --> 00:10:52,042
for blacks and other minorities
in the hotels of San Francisco.

155
00:10:52,168 --> 00:10:55,048
A picket line formed
around the Sheraton Palace,

156
00:10:55,171 --> 00:11:00,409
while negotiations with the Hotel
Owners Association took place inside.

157
00:11:01,458 --> 00:11:04,054
It was getting to the point
where we were saying,

158
00:11:04,182 --> 00:11:06,903
''We are going to create
a confrontation.''

159
00:11:07,024 --> 00:11:11,305
''We're going to create a situation
that's intolerable

160
00:11:11,429 --> 00:11:13,990
and we're going to force you
to respond to it.''

161
00:11:14,112 --> 00:11:17,470
''We're willing to get arrested
in order to do it.''

162
00:11:17,596 --> 00:11:20,031
''And now the ball's in your court.''

163
00:11:26,686 --> 00:11:31,366
All of us in this elegant lobby,
I can't convey to you the effect.

164
00:11:31,490 --> 00:11:34,609
It was like the riffraff
coming to the White House.

165
00:11:36,376 --> 00:11:39,370
The real democratic masses
had moved in and taken over,

166
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:42,141
saying, ''No, you cannot continue

167
00:11:42,263 --> 00:11:44,698
to run this hotel
in this racist fashion.''

168
00:11:44,825 --> 00:11:48,980
''The world is being redefined.
Things cannot continue on that way.''

169
00:11:49,110 --> 00:11:51,147
We just entered into discussions

170
00:11:51,272 --> 00:11:54,107
with the Sheraton Palace
for the last eight hours.

171
00:11:54,236 --> 00:11:56,228
We were given a seven-page document

172
00:11:56,358 --> 00:11:58,954
which was supposed
to summarise the agreement.

173
00:11:59,080 --> 00:12:02,996
But there was a hitch, the Sheraton
Palace wasn't willing to sign.

174
00:12:29,994 --> 00:12:33,386
It was the first major victory
of anything l'd been involved in.

175
00:12:33,518 --> 00:12:35,430
The Sheraton Palace Hotel arrests

176
00:12:35,560 --> 00:12:37,916
and convictions and trials
and so forth

177
00:12:38,042 --> 00:12:42,597
led to the first agreement, that
I knew of in the north, of its kind.

178
00:12:42,728 --> 00:12:46,280
That was an agreement
between the entire hotel industry

179
00:12:46,412 --> 00:12:49,053
and the ad hoc committee
to end discrimination,

180
00:12:49,175 --> 00:12:52,055
to hire minority individuals

181
00:12:52,178 --> 00:12:56,094
in all levels of employment,
including management.

182
00:12:56,222 --> 00:12:58,293
It was very historic
and very elevating

183
00:12:58,425 --> 00:13:00,735
and it really pumped us all up
to think,

184
00:13:00,868 --> 00:13:04,864
''My God, we really could have
an effect on history.''

185
00:13:04,992 --> 00:13:09,353
''We could have an effect on lives
of people we'd never know or meet.''

186
00:13:09,477 --> 00:13:14,191
It was simply by taking seriously
the words of the Constitution

187
00:13:14,322 --> 00:13:17,202
and the preamble
in The Declaration of lndependence

188
00:13:17,325 --> 00:13:20,877
and all that stuff that we believed
in with great vim and vigour.

189
00:13:21,009 --> 00:13:23,650
Here we just saw it happen
and it worked.

190
00:13:23,772 --> 00:13:26,128
It was a very thrilling experience
for us,

191
00:13:26,255 --> 00:13:30,092
but the flip side of it is other people
saw it in a different light.

192
00:13:30,219 --> 00:13:34,614
That is, the business community
saw it as a threat,

193
00:13:34,744 --> 00:13:37,340
as something
that would cause them problems.

194
00:13:37,467 --> 00:13:40,586
The fact that 1 00 Berkeley students
were arrested,

195
00:13:40,711 --> 00:13:46,154
probably 500, 600, 800 Berkeley students
were involved in the thing,

196
00:13:46,276 --> 00:13:48,108
it was a portent of things to come.

197
00:13:48,239 --> 00:13:51,119
Very quickly pressure
was put on the university.

198
00:13:51,242 --> 00:13:54,441
''You've got to stop this.''
The terms that were used were,

199
00:13:54,566 --> 00:13:59,086
''The university cannot be used
as a base for attacks on the community.''

200
00:14:00,452 --> 00:14:03,810
In the fall of the school year '64-'65,

201
00:14:03,936 --> 00:14:07,898
we returned to campus to find out
the tables on Bancroft and Telegraph

202
00:14:08,021 --> 00:14:12,860
which had historically been
the campus political activity lifeline

203
00:14:12,985 --> 00:14:14,384
were banned.

204
00:14:14,507 --> 00:14:18,105
Tables have been permitted
out in front of Bancroft and Telegraph

205
00:14:18,231 --> 00:14:22,113
to distribute literature,

206
00:14:22,235 --> 00:14:26,026
including the ideas of policy
and advocating stands.

207
00:14:26,160 --> 00:14:28,960
At this particular point,
we have been denied this.

208
00:14:29,083 --> 00:14:32,840
We think,
whether or not this is true or not

209
00:14:32,967 --> 00:14:35,243
as far as why they're doing it,

210
00:14:35,369 --> 00:14:37,087
the effect of cutting this off

211
00:14:37,211 --> 00:14:39,680
is to stop political activity
on this campus.

212
00:14:39,814 --> 00:14:43,492
We knew at the time that it was aimed
at the civil rights movement

213
00:14:43,619 --> 00:14:45,576
and at progressive organisations

214
00:14:45,701 --> 00:14:49,139
and at those interested in
the peace movement and civil rights.

215
00:14:49,264 --> 00:14:50,822
Mainly civil rights.

216
00:14:50,946 --> 00:14:56,389
But by banning all of us,
they created an enormous reaction

217
00:14:56,513 --> 00:15:01,466
because they united a group of people
around the need to have those tables

218
00:15:01,598 --> 00:15:05,833
that couldn't have united themselves
under any other circumstances.

219
00:15:05,963 --> 00:15:09,116
We told them
they had to go back on the streets

220
00:15:09,246 --> 00:15:12,719
for this kind of activity.
They then took the position

221
00:15:12,851 --> 00:15:16,608
that, ''We want to undertake these
activities on campus property,''

222
00:15:16,734 --> 00:15:18,930
and we said, ''This is not possible.''

223
00:15:19,057 --> 00:15:22,769
When the university banned political
action at Bancroft and Telegraph,

224
00:15:22,901 --> 00:15:25,416
they said it was the same
as the rest of the campus.

225
00:15:25,544 --> 00:15:28,299
We said, ''If it's the same
as the rest of the campus,

226
00:15:28,427 --> 00:15:30,099
then we can do this anywhere.''

227
00:15:30,229 --> 00:15:32,744
We decided to move our tables
to Sather Gate.

228
00:15:32,872 --> 00:15:35,752
Five students were sitting at tables
and deans came by

229
00:15:35,875 --> 00:15:38,550
and said, ''If you don't leave,
we have to cite you.''

230
00:15:38,679 --> 00:15:41,240
One of the students said,
''I'm sorry, sir,

231
00:15:41,361 --> 00:15:44,196
my organisation
has not authorised me to leave.''

232
00:15:44,324 --> 00:15:45,962
And so he was cited.

233
00:15:46,086 --> 00:15:49,798
As soon as the student was cited,
the dean would cite the next student.

234
00:15:49,931 --> 00:15:51,763
Somebody would sit in their place.

235
00:15:51,893 --> 00:15:55,684
After they cited the five people,
they didn't want to be there all day,

236
00:15:55,816 --> 00:15:58,696
so the deans started leaving.
People said, ''Me, too!''

237
00:15:58,820 --> 00:16:03,420
At three o'clock, 500 people
marched into Sproul Hall saying,

238
00:16:03,545 --> 00:16:07,507
''Whatever you do to those people,
you've got to do to us.''

239
00:16:07,629 --> 00:16:11,021
If you don't stand up for your
freedom now, you're dead, guys.

240
00:16:13,956 --> 00:16:16,187
The deans wanted the students
who were cited

241
00:16:16,319 --> 00:16:17,798
to go into the deans' office.

242
00:16:17,921 --> 00:16:21,154
We said, ''We all did it.
You have to treat us all the same.''

243
00:16:21,284 --> 00:16:24,642
We were out in the halls
and nobody would go into the office.

244
00:16:24,768 --> 00:16:28,160
At about nine o'clock,
they announced that those five people

245
00:16:28,292 --> 00:16:31,013
plus three demonstration leaders
were suspended.

246
00:16:31,135 --> 00:16:34,254
The next morning, we really knew
it was going to happen.

247
00:16:34,378 --> 00:16:36,939
We set our tables up
in front of Sproul Hall.

248
00:16:37,061 --> 00:16:40,499
I guess I was one of the more noisy
people so a dean came up to me.

249
00:16:40,625 --> 00:16:43,903
He asked me to identify myself
and I refused.

250
00:16:44,029 --> 00:16:47,911
He said if I didn't identify myself,
I would be arrested.

251
00:16:48,033 --> 00:16:51,711
It wasn't the first time that
I had been threatened with arrest.

252
00:16:51,837 --> 00:16:54,306
Two policemen took me under the arms.
I went limp.

253
00:16:54,440 --> 00:16:56,511
They dragged me into the police car.

254
00:16:56,643 --> 00:17:00,161
Before I got into the police car,
it was surrounded with people.

255
00:17:02,248 --> 00:17:04,080
It was two minutes to 1 2.

256
00:17:04,211 --> 00:17:05,883
There's a commotion going on.

257
00:17:06,013 --> 00:17:08,813
Some people are joining in
or stopping to watch.

258
00:17:08,936 --> 00:17:11,053
This police car is going nowhere.

259
00:17:12,100 --> 00:17:14,661
I just did
what any of my fellow students

260
00:17:14,782 --> 00:17:18,300
or fellows in other organisations
would've done.

261
00:17:18,426 --> 00:17:21,579
I was just singled out.
Chance selected me. l'm no martyr.

262
00:17:21,710 --> 00:17:25,786
I couldn't understand why people were
prohibited from speaking in the plaza.

263
00:17:25,915 --> 00:17:29,593
And if this demonstration
around this police car

264
00:17:29,718 --> 00:17:34,079
was some way to indicate it was wrong,
it seemed like a good idea.

265
00:17:34,203 --> 00:17:37,356
I didn't like the idea
of seizing a police car very much

266
00:17:37,487 --> 00:17:40,083
but it was certainly a peaceful seizing.

267
00:17:40,209 --> 00:17:42,041
People began to speak.

268
00:17:42,172 --> 00:17:45,770
The only reason I took part in this
is because I like Cal very much.

269
00:17:45,896 --> 00:17:47,967
l'd like to see it better.

270
00:17:50,101 --> 00:17:53,858
And they'd stand on the car.
People were very careful about the car.

271
00:17:53,984 --> 00:17:58,105
People would take their shoes off
and gently climb up on the car.

272
00:17:58,229 --> 00:18:02,111
They moved from the hood of the car
up onto the roof of the car.

273
00:18:02,234 --> 00:18:05,786
Then the argument raged.
Are you with us or against us?

274
00:18:05,917 --> 00:18:09,070
I wasn't either. I was watching
and listening to speeches.

275
00:18:09,201 --> 00:18:12,275
There was an open microphone
on top of the police car.

276
00:18:12,405 --> 00:18:14,966
Anybody who wanted to speak
signed up on a list.

277
00:18:15,088 --> 00:18:18,241
They had three minutes
to say anything they wanted.

278
00:18:18,371 --> 00:18:22,003
Hour after hour,
people were getting up and orating.

279
00:18:22,135 --> 00:18:25,209
It was like an explosion of ideas.

280
00:18:25,339 --> 00:18:27,057
Aristotle said,

281
00:18:27,181 --> 00:18:30,300
''lf you are not a citizen,
you are either a beast or a god!''

282
00:18:30,424 --> 00:18:33,020
Now, I ask you a very simple question...

283
00:18:34,748 --> 00:18:39,029
People start talking,
bringing in the Greek philosophers,

284
00:18:39,154 --> 00:18:42,387
the French Revolution,
talking about all the ideas,

285
00:18:42,517 --> 00:18:45,716
constitutional liberties,
as if they had meaning.

286
00:18:45,840 --> 00:18:49,039
Late at night
some fraternity people came down.

287
00:18:49,164 --> 00:18:51,520
There was some confrontation.

288
00:18:51,647 --> 00:18:55,325
They were heckling from the back
so someone said, ''Come on up.''

289
00:18:55,451 --> 00:18:59,606
They got one of the fraternity boys
to say his thing on the mic.

290
00:18:59,735 --> 00:19:01,214
By the time he got there,

291
00:19:01,337 --> 00:19:04,615
he forgot why he was against it
and his friends booed him.

292
00:19:04,741 --> 00:19:07,621
It really was a political awakening.

293
00:19:07,745 --> 00:19:10,625
There was a political issue
and we were all part of this.

294
00:19:10,748 --> 00:19:12,740
We weren't observing it
on television.

295
00:19:12,870 --> 00:19:15,180
We were part of deciding
what would happen,

296
00:19:15,312 --> 00:19:17,987
as was the university administration.

297
00:19:18,116 --> 00:19:21,349
No one from the university
administration came to speak.

298
00:19:21,480 --> 00:19:24,201
No one came to present
any reasoned point of view

299
00:19:24,323 --> 00:19:26,201
about why the arrest had occurred

300
00:19:26,324 --> 00:19:31,038
or why the rules restricting
political speech were justifiable.

301
00:19:31,170 --> 00:19:32,728
Nothing.

302
00:19:33,773 --> 00:19:36,812
I ended up sitting in that police car
for 32 hours

303
00:19:36,936 --> 00:19:41,012
and, at the maximum time,
there were as many as 6,000 people

304
00:19:41,140 --> 00:19:43,336
sitting down around the police car.

305
00:19:43,463 --> 00:19:46,343
At various points
when arrests were threatened,

306
00:19:46,466 --> 00:19:49,221
people didn't run away.
More people sat down.

307
00:19:49,350 --> 00:19:51,706
People felt they had to sit down.

308
00:19:51,832 --> 00:19:54,267
People were saying,
''Join us. Join us.''

309
00:20:07,249 --> 00:20:11,929
Mario and a delegation is off
negotiating with the administration.

310
00:20:12,054 --> 00:20:16,335
At the final minute, they arrive
and a settlement has been reached.

311
00:20:16,459 --> 00:20:18,735
May I please have a decision?

312
00:20:22,665 --> 00:20:24,337
What's the word now?

313
00:20:24,468 --> 00:20:27,746
- There's been an agreement signed.
- An agreement signed?

314
00:20:27,871 --> 00:20:31,662
Yes, by the student groups and by me,
as president of the university,

315
00:20:31,795 --> 00:20:33,991
which has several points to it.

316
00:20:34,118 --> 00:20:37,875
The first point
is that the student demonstrators

317
00:20:38,002 --> 00:20:43,843
shall desist
from their illegal actions,

318
00:20:43,968 --> 00:20:46,199
protesting university regulations.

319
00:20:46,331 --> 00:20:52,286
We've also agreed to set up
a committee to examine the rules.

320
00:20:52,418 --> 00:20:55,173
The remarkable thing
about this entire situation

321
00:20:55,301 --> 00:20:59,058
is that there's been a coalition,
that I think is unusual in politics.

322
00:20:59,185 --> 00:21:04,309
A coalition from Youth for Goldwater
to the Young Socialist Alliance.

323
00:21:04,431 --> 00:21:06,992
Usually these groups
don't speak together,

324
00:21:07,114 --> 00:21:11,156
let alone sit on the same table
and work out policies and platforms.

325
00:21:11,278 --> 00:21:15,433
l'm proud to say that American students
are united on one issue

326
00:21:15,563 --> 00:21:19,320
and that's the First Amendment
privileges of freedom of speech,

327
00:21:19,447 --> 00:21:22,999
the right to advocate and discuss
at any time, at any place,

328
00:21:23,130 --> 00:21:26,842
as long as it doesn't disturb
classes and interfere with traffic.

329
00:21:26,975 --> 00:21:32,418
Our meetings lasted
1 0, 1 2, 1 5, 1 8 hours.

330
00:21:32,541 --> 00:21:37,061
People slept at different times
during some of them and came back

331
00:21:37,186 --> 00:21:40,624
because we had two goals,
to figure out what to do

332
00:21:40,750 --> 00:21:43,505
and to try to keep
this enormous coalition together.

333
00:21:43,633 --> 00:21:47,185
Understanding the power
of all of these groups

334
00:21:47,317 --> 00:21:50,072
moving in the same direction
around this issue.

335
00:21:50,200 --> 00:21:54,595
That takes a long time because
you can't do it by a majority vote.

336
00:21:54,725 --> 00:21:57,480
The minority just says,
''OK, l'm gone.''

337
00:21:57,608 --> 00:22:00,807
It had to be by consensus.
People had to agree.

338
00:22:00,932 --> 00:22:02,206
And it took forever.

339
00:22:02,334 --> 00:22:06,376
We called it boring, disgusting,
time-consuming democracy.

340
00:22:07,098 --> 00:22:11,060
I remember one administrator
described the Free Speech Movement

341
00:22:11,183 --> 00:22:13,618
as a civil rights panty raid.

342
00:22:13,746 --> 00:22:16,022
That's not such a dumb description.

343
00:22:16,148 --> 00:22:19,301
He did see kids having a good time.
It was very exciting.

344
00:22:19,432 --> 00:22:23,223
Instead of being about panties,
it's about civil rights.

345
00:22:23,356 --> 00:22:25,473
But what he failed to see

346
00:22:25,599 --> 00:22:29,356
is that there was a real underlying
seriousness to this.

347
00:22:29,482 --> 00:22:32,362
There was a tremendous
sense of community.

348
00:22:32,486 --> 00:22:36,243
It's as if all these students
had been waiting to work together

349
00:22:36,370 --> 00:22:37,883
and suddenly they did it.

350
00:22:38,012 --> 00:22:39,969
Six weeks ago, they promised us

351
00:22:40,095 --> 00:22:43,647
that they would negotiate
on their regulations of free speech.

352
00:22:43,778 --> 00:22:47,694
Yes, they negotiated. They have
blocked every attempt we have made.

353
00:22:47,823 --> 00:22:49,701
If they refuse to come to a stand,

354
00:22:49,825 --> 00:22:53,058
we will also consider negotiations
as being broken by them.

355
00:22:53,189 --> 00:22:55,306
However we will continue to try

356
00:22:55,430 --> 00:22:59,062
and get them to come to a vote
or take a stand or make a decision.

357
00:22:59,195 --> 00:23:02,155
As Mario Savio
would talk about a meeting

358
00:23:02,278 --> 00:23:04,235
and tell what happened in the meeting

359
00:23:04,361 --> 00:23:07,400
and explain the positions
taken by the administration

360
00:23:07,524 --> 00:23:11,076
and, from what I could tell, would
tell exactly what had gone on,...

361
00:23:13,450 --> 00:23:18,209
..l would then contrast that with
the administration's explanation.

362
00:23:18,336 --> 00:23:21,375
Muffled, guarded.

363
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:25,018
The administration would not explain
what had happened.

364
00:23:25,143 --> 00:23:26,896
They wouldn't tell the truth.

365
00:23:27,025 --> 00:23:29,335
A lot of people became very upset

366
00:23:29,468 --> 00:23:32,826
about what administration spokesmen
would say was going on

367
00:23:32,952 --> 00:23:35,023
when they knew it wasn't true.

368
00:23:35,153 --> 00:23:36,472
What you have there

369
00:23:36,595 --> 00:23:41,468
are a few of these rather bearded,
unwashed characters

370
00:23:41,601 --> 00:23:44,481
with sandals and long hair

371
00:23:44,604 --> 00:23:49,124
who normally would be regarded
tolerantly as a lunatic fringe

372
00:23:49,249 --> 00:23:53,165
which you put up with
but you do not necessarily encourage.

373
00:23:53,293 --> 00:23:57,209
In effect, the campus has been
turned over to these characters.

374
00:23:57,338 --> 00:24:01,095
Somewhere in the process of the FSM,
for the very first time

375
00:24:01,222 --> 00:24:06,699
the young, privileged,
affluent children of the culture

376
00:24:06,828 --> 00:24:10,710
began to see themselves
as an oppressed class.

377
00:24:10,833 --> 00:24:13,268
It was an astounding perception

378
00:24:13,396 --> 00:24:16,948
because here we were
at the height of the privileged,

379
00:24:17,079 --> 00:24:19,435
the best students
at the best multiversity

380
00:24:19,562 --> 00:24:21,918
destined to be the managers
of the society.

381
00:24:22,045 --> 00:24:24,002
In the middle of this,

382
00:24:24,127 --> 00:24:27,087
we turned around
and looked at our education and said,

383
00:24:27,211 --> 00:24:30,523
''Wait a minute.
Somehow the best is the worst.''

384
00:24:30,654 --> 00:24:32,930
It put us out of touch
with the society.

385
00:24:33,056 --> 00:24:37,177
It severed technology from values,
the intellect from the heart.

386
00:24:37,301 --> 00:24:40,579
For many people, this was
the only educational activity

387
00:24:40,704 --> 00:24:44,302
that we were involved in
that was deeply meaningful.

388
00:25:49,739 --> 00:25:52,174
In late November, it became clear

389
00:25:52,302 --> 00:25:54,977
that the administration
had finally figured out

390
00:25:55,105 --> 00:25:57,780
how to break us apart as a coalition.

391
00:25:57,909 --> 00:26:00,823
That was they said
we could have our tables back.

392
00:26:00,951 --> 00:26:02,829
We could do the things we wanted to

393
00:26:02,954 --> 00:26:05,515
but we couldn't advocate
unlawful activity,

394
00:26:05,637 --> 00:26:09,918
less we'd still be liable for
discipline as students on the campus.

395
00:26:10,042 --> 00:26:11,999
It was very clear to us

396
00:26:12,124 --> 00:26:15,482
that the only groups that last part
of the rule were aimed at

397
00:26:15,607 --> 00:26:19,159
were those who used civil disobedience
in their strategies.

398
00:26:19,291 --> 00:26:22,046
That meant the left
and the civil rights movement.

399
00:26:22,175 --> 00:26:23,574
We felt quite defeated.

400
00:26:23,697 --> 00:26:25,973
This position on the question
of advocacy,

401
00:26:26,098 --> 00:26:29,297
which the president recommended
and the regents approved,

402
00:26:29,422 --> 00:26:32,860
is far severer than any recommended
by any faculty committee

403
00:26:32,986 --> 00:26:36,139
and, of course, is totally unacceptable
to the students.

404
00:26:36,270 --> 00:26:39,902
It constitutes, in fact,
prior restraint on speech,

405
00:26:40,033 --> 00:26:42,070
on political expression on campus.

406
00:26:42,196 --> 00:26:44,631
So, you've lost a lot of ground?

407
00:26:44,759 --> 00:26:48,516
Well, it's very hard to say.

408
00:26:48,643 --> 00:26:51,876
Fortunately, the university
committed another atrocity.

409
00:26:52,007 --> 00:26:56,527
They could not end this whole incident
without punishing somebody

410
00:26:56,652 --> 00:27:00,443
and teaching a lesson
that this should never again happen.

411
00:27:00,576 --> 00:27:03,615
So when students got back
after Thanksgiving break,

412
00:27:03,740 --> 00:27:06,814
they found out that the eight people
originally cited

413
00:27:06,943 --> 00:27:10,621
had received letters saying
that disciplinary proceedings

414
00:27:10,747 --> 00:27:13,388
leading to expulsion
had begun against them.

415
00:27:14,311 --> 00:27:17,623
So here we are.
Four students are getting the axe,

416
00:27:17,755 --> 00:27:21,910
six organisations are getting the axe
for standing up this semester

417
00:27:22,039 --> 00:27:24,395
and for fighting for these things.

418
00:27:24,522 --> 00:27:29,441
They're getting the axe not for what
they did but for what we have done.

419
00:27:29,568 --> 00:27:32,403
They spoke for us.
They were part of us.

420
00:27:32,530 --> 00:27:35,205
They have been singled out
and will be chopped off.

421
00:27:35,333 --> 00:27:37,131
We were told the following.

422
00:27:37,256 --> 00:27:42,574
If Kerr tried to get something
more liberal out of the regents,

423
00:27:42,702 --> 00:27:45,662
why didn't he make a public statement
to that effect?

424
00:27:45,785 --> 00:27:47,184
The answer we received

425
00:27:47,306 --> 00:27:50,106
from a well-meaning liberal
was the following.

426
00:27:50,230 --> 00:27:54,351
He said, ''Would you ever imagine
the manager of a firm

427
00:27:54,475 --> 00:27:58,312
making a statement publicly
in opposition to his directors?''

428
00:27:58,438 --> 00:28:00,395
That's the answer.

429
00:28:00,521 --> 00:28:03,754
I ask you to consider
if this is a firm

430
00:28:03,885 --> 00:28:06,354
and if the regents are the directors

431
00:28:06,488 --> 00:28:08,923
and if President Kerr is the manager,

432
00:28:09,051 --> 00:28:12,524
then, I tell you something,
the faculty are a bunch of employees

433
00:28:12,654 --> 00:28:15,807
and we're the raw materials,
but we're raw materials

434
00:28:15,938 --> 00:28:18,898
that don't mean
to have any process upon us,

435
00:28:19,021 --> 00:28:20,899
don't mean to be made into a product,

436
00:28:21,023 --> 00:28:25,976
don't mean to end up being bought
by some clients of the university,

437
00:28:26,108 --> 00:28:29,865
be they the government, industry,
organised labour, be they anyone.

438
00:28:29,993 --> 00:28:31,108
We're human beings.

439
00:28:34,238 --> 00:28:39,442
There's a time when the operation
of the machine becomes so odious,

440
00:28:39,563 --> 00:28:43,081
makes you so sick at heart
that you can't take part.

441
00:28:43,207 --> 00:28:45,483
You can't even passively take part.

442
00:28:45,610 --> 00:28:49,208
You've got to put your bodies
upon the gears and upon the wheels,

443
00:28:49,334 --> 00:28:53,091
upon the levers, upon the apparatus
and you've got to make it stop

444
00:28:53,218 --> 00:28:56,212
and you've got to indicate
to the people who run it

445
00:28:56,341 --> 00:28:57,740
that unless you're free,

446
00:28:57,863 --> 00:29:00,902
the machine will be prevented
from working at all.

447
00:29:40,870 --> 00:29:43,021
How could you not
go into Sproul Hall?

448
00:29:43,153 --> 00:29:46,511
Everybody was going into Sproul Hall.
It was a...

449
00:29:48,678 --> 00:29:51,193
It was a...

450
00:29:52,282 --> 00:29:54,717
What other alternative did you have

451
00:29:54,845 --> 00:29:58,157
to say that you weren't happy
with the way things were going?

452
00:29:58,288 --> 00:30:01,886
I hesitated for about two seconds
and I thought...

453
00:30:02,012 --> 00:30:06,167
I got a picture of my husband's face
and I thought,

454
00:30:06,297 --> 00:30:08,732
''What is this going to do?''

455
00:30:08,860 --> 00:30:12,492
''What is it going to do to my career,
to my life?''

456
00:30:12,624 --> 00:30:16,016
Then I just said, ''To hell with it,
I don't care what it does.''

457
00:30:16,148 --> 00:30:18,789
''This is my chance to do something.''

458
00:30:19,832 --> 00:30:24,705
The fourth, third and second floors
are filled. Stay downstairs.

459
00:30:24,837 --> 00:30:29,835
Members of the Bay Area Civil Rights
Movement in the stairwell over there.

460
00:30:43,537 --> 00:30:47,294
People were dancing in the hallways.
People were studying.

461
00:30:47,422 --> 00:30:49,983
People were just sitting
on the cold floors,

462
00:30:50,104 --> 00:30:52,859
wandering around,
talking with each other.

463
00:30:53,748 --> 00:30:58,621
It was chaos and confusion
and it was sort of like a party

464
00:30:58,754 --> 00:31:00,950
and it went on and on and on.

465
00:31:01,077 --> 00:31:04,993
Finally, the police decided
that if you wanted to go out,

466
00:31:05,120 --> 00:31:08,034
you could go out,
but you couldn't get back in.

467
00:31:09,606 --> 00:31:11,563
I debated about this for...

468
00:31:11,688 --> 00:31:15,240
I don't think I was in the position
of deciding to make witness

469
00:31:15,372 --> 00:31:18,571
or not make witness,
a great moral decision.

470
00:31:18,695 --> 00:31:23,933
It was getting to be dinnertime.
It was getting in or not getting in.

471
00:31:24,061 --> 00:31:27,135
I had no idea this was going
to go on for a long time.

472
00:31:27,265 --> 00:31:28,664
When I came back,

473
00:31:28,786 --> 00:31:31,985
people were climbing with ropes
up the front of Sproul Hall.

474
00:31:32,110 --> 00:31:36,794
It was clear that something was
happening but it wasn't clear what.

475
00:31:36,995 --> 00:31:40,468
May I have your attention, please?

476
00:31:42,801 --> 00:31:48,722
I am Dr Edward Strong,
chancellor of the Berkeley campus.

477
00:31:51,411 --> 00:31:53,448
I have an announcement.

478
00:31:54,895 --> 00:31:59,130
This assemblage
has developed to such a point

479
00:31:59,259 --> 00:32:02,014
that the purpose
and work of the university

480
00:32:02,142 --> 00:32:05,375
have been materially impaired.

481
00:32:16,278 --> 00:32:18,554
Please go.

482
00:32:18,681 --> 00:32:21,436
I wanted to run.
My impulse was to run.

483
00:32:21,563 --> 00:32:25,320
I was hanging on to the people next
to me to keep myself from jumping up.

484
00:32:25,447 --> 00:32:28,122
Then something really neat happened.

485
00:32:28,251 --> 00:32:35,653
That was... Art Goldberg
was the leader of our floor.

486
00:32:35,778 --> 00:32:38,213
He was in charge of us.
He was standing there.

487
00:32:38,341 --> 00:32:40,298
He heard they were coming up

488
00:32:40,424 --> 00:32:43,384
so he was giving us a speech
on what you do,

489
00:32:43,507 --> 00:32:44,860
how you go limp.

490
00:32:44,989 --> 00:32:48,063
He said, ''When the cops come at you,
don't fight them.''

491
00:32:48,192 --> 00:32:49,910
''You just want to go limp.''

492
00:32:50,034 --> 00:32:53,187
As he's saying this,
the cops are coming at him.

493
00:32:53,318 --> 00:32:55,355
He talked all the way down
to the floor.

494
00:32:55,480 --> 00:32:58,315
I know this because I was looking
between their legs.

495
00:32:58,444 --> 00:33:00,561
It was really an inspiration.

496
00:33:00,686 --> 00:33:04,364
I said, ''lf he can do that,
that's what l'm going to try to do.''

497
00:33:04,490 --> 00:33:06,208
When they got to me, they said,

498
00:33:06,332 --> 00:33:09,167
''Do you want to walk out like a lady
or get dragged out?''

499
00:33:09,295 --> 00:33:11,685
I said, ''l want to get dragged out
like a lady.''

500
00:33:42,411 --> 00:33:46,966
With the arrests came
a massive collapse of the authority

501
00:33:47,096 --> 00:33:48,849
of the campus administration.

502
00:33:48,978 --> 00:33:52,735
Now, they made a desperate attempt
to regain that authority

503
00:33:52,863 --> 00:33:56,336
in a big meeting
at the Greek Theater.

504
00:33:56,466 --> 00:34:00,223
The departmental chairmen believe
that the acts of civil disobedience

505
00:34:00,350 --> 00:34:02,865
on December 2nd and 3rd
were unwarranted

506
00:34:02,993 --> 00:34:06,305
and that they obstruct rational
and fair consideration

507
00:34:06,437 --> 00:34:09,112
of the grievances
brought forward by the students.

508
00:34:09,240 --> 00:34:12,792
There are a small number
of individuals, I regret to say,

509
00:34:12,924 --> 00:34:17,683
who are interested in fomenting
a crisis merely for the sake of crisis.

510
00:34:19,091 --> 00:34:23,566
They hope that continuing chaos
will bring about a total revolution

511
00:34:23,695 --> 00:34:26,894
and their own particular concept
of utopia.

512
00:34:32,786 --> 00:34:36,668
The university supports
the powers of persuasion

513
00:34:36,790 --> 00:34:38,941
against the use of force,

514
00:34:39,072 --> 00:34:43,752
the constructive act
as against the destructive blow,

515
00:34:43,878 --> 00:34:48,876
respect for the rights of others,
opposition to passion and hate,

516
00:34:49,003 --> 00:34:53,523
the reasoned argument
as against the simplistic slogan.

517
00:34:53,648 --> 00:34:57,929
The academic world
and the people of this state

518
00:34:58,053 --> 00:35:01,605
expect of us conduct commensurate

519
00:35:01,736 --> 00:35:05,698
with our past achievements
and our high capacities.

520
00:35:05,821 --> 00:35:09,703
We should expect no less of ourselves.
Thank you.

521
00:35:19,636 --> 00:35:21,867
We want Mario!

522
00:35:26,243 --> 00:35:28,553
The police have got Mario.

523
00:35:28,686 --> 00:35:31,121
They are pulling him away...

524
00:35:31,249 --> 00:35:34,607
The police have pulled Mario away
from the speaker stand.

525
00:35:41,540 --> 00:35:44,898
He tried to exercise free speech.

526
00:35:45,024 --> 00:35:48,302
When he stood up here,
the police took him away.

527
00:35:48,428 --> 00:35:51,740
That shows the entire process
that's going on campus.

528
00:35:51,872 --> 00:35:53,909
We, of course, had no notion

529
00:35:54,033 --> 00:35:57,995
that Mr Savio was going to try to
speak at the end of this meeting.

530
00:35:58,118 --> 00:36:00,474
He asked... Just a moment.

531
00:36:00,601 --> 00:36:04,517
Just a moment. He asked...

532
00:36:05,365 --> 00:36:08,518
- Just a moment.
- Just let him speak.

533
00:36:08,649 --> 00:36:10,082
He asked...

534
00:36:12,093 --> 00:36:14,848
He asked me at the beginning
of the meeting

535
00:36:14,976 --> 00:36:18,209
whether he would be allowed
to speak at this meeting.

536
00:36:18,339 --> 00:36:19,488
I said he would not

537
00:36:19,621 --> 00:36:22,854
because this was a structured meeting,
not an open forum,

538
00:36:22,985 --> 00:36:26,138
and we had a programme
which had been approved.

539
00:36:26,268 --> 00:36:28,180
They're hypocrites and bastards.

540
00:36:28,311 --> 00:36:32,387
Even if the Greek Theater
had gone exactly according to plan,

541
00:36:32,515 --> 00:36:34,472
it still would've been a flop.

542
00:36:34,597 --> 00:36:37,716
But it was worse than a flop,
it was a fiasco,

543
00:36:37,841 --> 00:36:40,596
and there was a kind of pandemonium
on the campus.

544
00:36:40,724 --> 00:36:43,159
There was a power vacuum.

545
00:36:43,287 --> 00:36:45,722
Who the hell was in charge?
Nobody knew.

546
00:36:45,849 --> 00:36:48,410
A bunch of us drafted a resolution.

547
00:36:48,532 --> 00:36:52,210
We took that resolution
into the academic senate

548
00:36:52,337 --> 00:36:54,772
and it passed by over seven to one.

549
00:36:54,900 --> 00:36:57,461
The overwhelming majority of the faculty

550
00:36:57,583 --> 00:37:01,784
had come down firmly
on the side of free speech.

551
00:37:01,907 --> 00:37:04,422
So when the faculty marched out

552
00:37:04,550 --> 00:37:08,148
into this cheering mob of students,

553
00:37:08,274 --> 00:37:11,234
we knew that was it,
that was victory.

554
00:37:11,357 --> 00:37:16,037
We had achieved everything
we had set out to achieve in the FSM.

555
00:37:16,162 --> 00:37:19,076
Student rallies
at the University of California

556
00:37:19,206 --> 00:37:22,166
over the past two months
have become commonplace.

557
00:37:22,289 --> 00:37:27,652
But today's rally in front of Sproul
Hall has taken on a different tone.

558
00:37:27,775 --> 00:37:30,165
Several thousand students
have gathered

559
00:37:30,298 --> 00:37:33,337
for what has been billed
as a victory celebration,

560
00:37:33,461 --> 00:37:35,930
a victory the students feel is assured

561
00:37:36,064 --> 00:37:40,219
as a result of yesterday's action
by the academic senate.

562
00:37:40,348 --> 00:37:45,632
We're asking that there be
no restrictions

563
00:37:45,754 --> 00:37:50,912
on the content of speech,
save those provided by the courts.

564
00:37:51,040 --> 00:37:54,432
That's an enormous amount of freedom.

565
00:37:55,525 --> 00:38:01,321
People can say things
within that area of freedom

566
00:38:01,452 --> 00:38:03,489
which are not responsible.

567
00:38:03,613 --> 00:38:07,529
Now, that's... We've finally
gotten into a position

568
00:38:07,658 --> 00:38:10,458
where we have to consider
being responsible

569
00:38:10,581 --> 00:38:14,942
because now we have the freedom
within which to be responsible.

570
00:38:15,066 --> 00:38:19,028
l'd like to say
that at this time l'm confident...

571
00:38:19,871 --> 00:38:22,432
l'm confident that the students

572
00:38:22,554 --> 00:38:25,753
and the faculty
in the University of California

573
00:38:25,878 --> 00:38:28,713
will exercise their freedom

574
00:38:28,841 --> 00:38:33,076
with the same responsibility
they've shown in winning their freedom.

575
00:38:35,007 --> 00:38:39,322
People thought, ''This is it.
This is day one of a new era.''

576
00:38:39,453 --> 00:38:42,447
We're going to have
a different university.

577
00:38:42,576 --> 00:38:45,695
We can re-plan the whole
structure of the university.

578
00:38:45,819 --> 00:38:49,497
If we want, we can have the
administrators sweeping sidewalks.

579
00:38:49,623 --> 00:38:52,092
That was a popular slogan
in those days.

580
00:38:52,226 --> 00:38:55,265
We can have a different
conception of education.

581
00:38:55,390 --> 00:38:58,623
Worse yet, we attracted to Berkeley

582
00:38:58,753 --> 00:39:02,385
the worst collection
of kooks and nuts you've ever seen.

583
00:39:02,517 --> 00:39:04,349
Everybody saw this on television

584
00:39:04,480 --> 00:39:06,915
and they had
a distorted conception of it.

585
00:39:07,043 --> 00:39:11,085
They thought what you do is you go to
Berkeley, riot and have a great time.

586
00:39:11,206 --> 00:39:15,168
lt's one big political,
sexual, drug feast.

587
00:39:15,291 --> 00:39:17,726
Didn't Ronald Reagan
himself say

588
00:39:17,854 --> 00:39:20,893
that it was all drugs and sex
and radical politics?

589
00:39:21,018 --> 00:39:24,012
They had this absurd conception
of what was going on.

590
00:39:24,140 --> 00:39:27,020
The media exaggerated it
in a certain way.

591
00:39:27,144 --> 00:39:31,220
We had created a set of expectations
that were really not satisfiable.

592
00:39:31,349 --> 00:39:34,981
What irritated me most in the stuff
that came out about that period

593
00:39:35,113 --> 00:39:38,425
was the description of us
as alienated and cynical.

594
00:39:38,556 --> 00:39:41,311
We were the absolute antithesis
of that.

595
00:39:41,439 --> 00:39:43,590
We were so committed and so involved,

596
00:39:43,722 --> 00:39:46,761
we risked our careers,
our jobs, our education

597
00:39:46,886 --> 00:39:51,167
and we did it because
we were so tied into this system,

598
00:39:51,290 --> 00:39:53,327
to this country, to this culture.

599
00:39:53,452 --> 00:39:55,603
We believed in it so much

600
00:39:55,735 --> 00:39:58,045
that we were willing
to take those risks

601
00:39:58,178 --> 00:40:00,534
at a time when it wasn't
popular to do so.

602
00:40:00,661 --> 00:40:04,976
l'd never realised people would lie
to maintain their positions of power.

603
00:40:05,705 --> 00:40:07,458
Then I saw it.

604
00:40:07,588 --> 00:40:11,550
I don't think people were evil to lie,
but they did it.

605
00:40:11,672 --> 00:40:16,192
They altered the way things were
to maintain their positions of power

606
00:40:16,317 --> 00:40:18,786
and they did it in a way
that was wrong.

607
00:40:18,920 --> 00:40:22,677
And then I saw that,
then I saw that everywhere.

608
00:40:22,804 --> 00:40:26,846
I saw that in the structures
of political power in Oakland.

609
00:40:26,969 --> 00:40:30,521
I saw that in the structures
of political power in the South.

610
00:40:30,652 --> 00:40:33,646
I began to see
that the mechanisms

611
00:40:33,776 --> 00:40:36,895
that the Free Speech Movement
was attempting to change

612
00:40:37,020 --> 00:40:39,455
were mechanisms
that operated everywhere.

613
00:40:39,583 --> 00:40:42,144
I was at a rally
where Mario was speaking.

614
00:40:42,265 --> 00:40:43,744
He was the speaker.

615
00:40:43,867 --> 00:40:46,906
It was some kind of wrap-up rally.

616
00:40:47,030 --> 00:40:50,263
Maybe it was right after the trial
or something like that.

617
00:40:50,394 --> 00:40:53,388
It was sort of like,
''Well, the FSM is over.''

618
00:40:53,518 --> 00:40:56,478
''We've got it all.
That's all settled.''

619
00:40:56,600 --> 00:40:59,958
My feeling was, ''OK, that's settled.
I can go on with my life.''

620
00:41:00,084 --> 00:41:03,841
I was even walking away from
the rally before Mario was finished.

621
00:41:03,969 --> 00:41:08,808
I have this very clear memory
of his voice ringing out

622
00:41:08,934 --> 00:41:10,891
as l'm leaving Sproul Plaza.

623
00:41:11,016 --> 00:41:15,377
He's saying, ''Don't walk away
because we've still got a war to stop.''

624
00:41:15,501 --> 00:41:20,739
I just looked around real startled
and I thought, ''War? What war?''

625
00:41:20,868 --> 00:41:23,623
Then it turned out
that it was the Vietnam War.

626
00:41:24,511 --> 00:41:29,795
If I can have your help,
if I can have your hand,

627
00:41:29,917 --> 00:41:34,631
if I can have your heart,
if I can have your prayers...

628
00:41:34,762 --> 00:41:37,801
If the good Lord is willing,
I will continue

629
00:41:37,925 --> 00:41:42,046
to try to lead this nation
and this world to peace.

630
00:42:13,084 --> 00:42:16,841
Victory in our struggle
for civil rights and free speech

631
00:42:16,967 --> 00:42:20,599
made us confident that we could
change the course of history.

632
00:42:21,453 --> 00:42:23,410
Then we learned about Vietnam

633
00:42:23,535 --> 00:42:26,574
and stopping the war
became our consuming cause.

634
00:42:30,502 --> 00:42:33,780
The first large activity
in opposition to the Vietnam War

635
00:42:33,906 --> 00:42:36,467
was Vietnam Day in May 1 965.

636
00:42:36,589 --> 00:42:40,551
There was a parade of speakers
that, one after another,

637
00:42:40,673 --> 00:42:43,906
started telling us
something that we really didn't know

638
00:42:44,037 --> 00:42:47,475
which was what our country
was doing in Vietnam.

639
00:42:47,601 --> 00:42:51,313
Most of us grew up thinking
that that United States

640
00:42:51,445 --> 00:42:54,200
was a great and humble nation

641
00:42:54,328 --> 00:42:59,566
that involved itself in the affairs
of other countries reluctantly

642
00:42:59,694 --> 00:43:02,608
as a last and final resort.

643
00:43:02,737 --> 00:43:05,811
But now, the war in Vietnam

644
00:43:05,941 --> 00:43:08,616
has provided
the incredibly sharp razor

645
00:43:08,743 --> 00:43:12,705
that has finally separated thousands
and thousands of people

646
00:43:12,828 --> 00:43:16,983
from their illusions
about the morality and integrity

647
00:43:17,113 --> 00:43:20,995
of this country's purposes
internationally.

648
00:43:21,117 --> 00:43:25,352
Never again will the self-righteous
saccharine moralism

649
00:43:25,482 --> 00:43:28,043
of promising a billion dollars
of economic aid

650
00:43:28,165 --> 00:43:32,127
while we spend billions and billions
of dollars to destroy them,

651
00:43:32,250 --> 00:43:36,485
never again will that moralism
have the power to persuade people

652
00:43:36,614 --> 00:43:40,166
of the essential decency
of this country's aims.

653
00:43:40,298 --> 00:43:42,654
What kind of a system is it

654
00:43:42,781 --> 00:43:48,782
that allows decent men, good men,
to make the decisions

655
00:43:48,907 --> 00:43:52,539
that have led to the thousands
and thousands of deaths

656
00:43:52,671 --> 00:43:54,549
that have happened in Vietnam?

657
00:43:54,674 --> 00:43:59,274
What kind of a system is it
that justifies the United States

658
00:43:59,398 --> 00:44:02,631
in seizing the destinies
of other people

659
00:44:02,762 --> 00:44:06,200
and using them callously
for our own ends?

660
00:44:06,326 --> 00:44:09,001
We must name that system

661
00:44:09,129 --> 00:44:11,690
and we must change it and control it,

662
00:44:11,812 --> 00:44:14,043
else it will destroy us.

663
00:44:18,299 --> 00:44:20,256
The war escalated rapidly.

664
00:44:20,381 --> 00:44:24,263
Every month another 20,000 soldiers
shipped out to Vietnam.

665
00:44:24,386 --> 00:44:26,821
Many of them came through Berkeley.

666
00:44:26,948 --> 00:44:29,783
Some of us decided to stop the trains.

667
00:44:30,833 --> 00:44:34,988
I was walking next to a woman
and she told me that she was a Buddhist

668
00:44:35,117 --> 00:44:38,077
and that she had been pulled into
stopping the war

669
00:44:38,201 --> 00:44:40,591
by the immolations of the priests.

670
00:44:40,723 --> 00:44:43,683
She said she was going
to sit on the tracks

671
00:44:43,807 --> 00:44:46,083
and so I said, ''OK, I will, too.''

672
00:44:47,170 --> 00:44:50,927
As the train came around the bend,
I thought, ''lt has to slow down.''

673
00:44:51,055 --> 00:44:52,808
But it sped up.

674
00:44:52,936 --> 00:44:56,328
Then as it got closer to us,
it began shooting out steam.

675
00:44:59,784 --> 00:45:03,017
As the steam hit me,
I jumped out of the steam.

676
00:45:03,148 --> 00:45:05,663
I looked at the woman
l'd been talking to

677
00:45:05,790 --> 00:45:09,832
and she was sitting in a full lotus
position in the middle of the tracks.

678
00:45:09,955 --> 00:45:14,316
As the train went rushing by,
I thought she was under it.

679
00:45:15,281 --> 00:45:19,243
When the train got past, I expected
to see a big pile of blood.

680
00:45:19,365 --> 00:45:22,200
There was nothing.
She had just disappeared.

681
00:45:24,090 --> 00:45:28,371
A few days later, the woman walked
into the museum where I was working,

682
00:45:28,495 --> 00:45:31,534
leading a big group of children
on a tour.

683
00:45:31,658 --> 00:45:36,178
I said, ''What happened?
What did you do?''

684
00:45:36,303 --> 00:45:38,864
She said,
''The plain-clothes policeman

685
00:45:38,986 --> 00:45:41,946
snatched me off the track
before the train got there.''

686
00:45:42,070 --> 00:45:44,426
I said,
''Were you going to stay there?''

687
00:45:44,552 --> 00:45:47,432
''Were you going to let the train
kill you?''

688
00:45:47,555 --> 00:45:50,788
She said, ''Yes, I was going to,
but that isn't what happened

689
00:45:50,919 --> 00:45:54,357
so now l'm here taking these children
through the museum.''

690
00:45:54,483 --> 00:45:57,956
And it really struck me.
It really hit my heart

691
00:45:58,087 --> 00:46:01,844
that here was a person
who was ready to give her life

692
00:46:01,971 --> 00:46:04,008
to try to stop the war.

693
00:46:04,134 --> 00:46:07,526
That's when it came through to me
just how important it was.

694
00:46:07,658 --> 00:46:10,811
What we have to do
is get rid of this tactical point.

695
00:46:10,940 --> 00:46:14,093
In the fall of '65,
the Vietnam Day Committee

696
00:46:14,224 --> 00:46:16,500
organised its first anti-war march.

697
00:46:16,627 --> 00:46:19,587
The destination
was the Oakland army terminal.

698
00:46:19,711 --> 00:46:23,627
The City of Oakland refused a permit.
The VDC voted to march anyway.

699
00:46:23,754 --> 00:46:27,386
All in favour of the motion
to march regardless of permit?

700
00:46:29,161 --> 00:46:30,799
All opposed?

701
00:46:32,444 --> 00:46:33,877
The Vietnam Day Committee

702
00:46:34,006 --> 00:46:36,806
intends to have a peaceful march
through Oakland.

703
00:46:36,929 --> 00:46:39,205
We intend no civil disobedience.

704
00:46:39,331 --> 00:46:43,373
We do not intend to break any laws.
We've made this point quite clear.

705
00:46:43,496 --> 00:46:46,456
We think it's incredible
that the Oakland authorities

706
00:46:46,580 --> 00:46:49,415
have denied us a permit
for this march.

707
00:46:49,543 --> 00:46:52,298
Our policy is the following.

708
00:46:52,425 --> 00:46:55,385
We are going to march
down Telegraph Avenue.

709
00:46:55,509 --> 00:46:57,944
We hear that a cordon

710
00:46:58,072 --> 00:47:02,627
is very likely to be formed
right past the Oakland City line.

711
00:47:02,757 --> 00:47:05,113
It is a very dangerous situation.

712
00:47:05,239 --> 00:47:08,199
We can create a great peace movement
or destroy it.

713
00:47:08,323 --> 00:47:10,440
We urge your cooperation.

714
00:47:11,406 --> 00:47:15,561
We had a problem. The police had put up
a barricade at the Oakland line.

715
00:47:15,691 --> 00:47:17,967
We had to deal
with what we were going to do

716
00:47:18,093 --> 00:47:20,289
