to allow you to wage the war.''

951
01:04:03,381 --> 01:04:05,134
''We're going to fight you.''

952
01:04:09,068 --> 01:04:12,700
Tuesday morning, the police came in,
wielding their clubs.

953
01:04:12,831 --> 01:04:14,230
They took us seriously.

954
01:04:14,353 --> 01:04:18,235
We said we were going to fight them,
so they fought us. lt was a disaster.

955
01:04:18,358 --> 01:04:21,511
We just melted. They wiped us out.

956
01:04:43,865 --> 01:04:45,936
Now it was, ''Here come the buses,

957
01:04:46,068 --> 01:04:49,905
and there is not a damn thing
you can do about it.''

958
01:04:50,031 --> 01:04:53,583
I began seeing all these young faces
in the windows going by me

959
01:04:53,716 --> 01:04:57,189
and I just wanted to reach out
and just grab them and stop them

960
01:04:57,320 --> 01:05:01,236
and say, ''Listen, this is your life
you're putting on the line here.''

961
01:05:01,365 --> 01:05:04,006
But what came out was, ''Don't go.''

962
01:05:12,777 --> 01:05:16,055
Join our lines. You don't have to go.
All you do is say no.

963
01:05:16,180 --> 01:05:19,458
Say no. You don't have to go.
You don't have to go.

964
01:05:19,584 --> 01:05:23,375
You don't have to go.
You don't have to go.

965
01:05:23,508 --> 01:05:27,026
There were bus-load after bus-load
after bus-load

966
01:05:27,152 --> 01:05:31,547
of young men that day,
and they were going off to die.

967
01:05:31,677 --> 01:05:34,671
And I remember
being physically sickened,

968
01:05:34,800 --> 01:05:41,518
realising that I couldn't affect
even that part of the war.

969
01:05:41,648 --> 01:05:44,483
Here I was, face to face
with these young men,

970
01:05:44,611 --> 01:05:48,402
and yet not one of them turned back.

971
01:05:48,535 --> 01:05:52,816
I don't think we stopped one inductee
from making that critical choice

972
01:05:52,940 --> 01:05:55,615
of stepping across the line
and going to Vietnam.

973
01:05:55,743 --> 01:05:59,659
I don't think we made one bit
of difference that day.

974
01:05:59,787 --> 01:06:03,260
- Does the demonstration bother you?
- No, I think it's funny.

975
01:06:03,391 --> 01:06:06,146
All them bums running round,
doing nothing.

976
01:06:11,440 --> 01:06:16,199
Tomorrow we go down there
twice as strong as we did today.

977
01:06:20,090 --> 01:06:24,610
We go down there with
twice as many shields as we did today,

978
01:06:24,734 --> 01:06:28,207
and we go down there
with everybody wearing one of these.

979
01:06:28,338 --> 01:06:30,091
If you can see the dents in there,

980
01:06:30,220 --> 01:06:32,451
I don't know
if you can see it from here,

981
01:06:32,583 --> 01:06:35,816
but that's what stands between me
and a cracked skull

982
01:06:35,946 --> 01:06:38,746
from the highway patrol
of the state of California.

983
01:06:38,870 --> 01:06:41,864
- Where do we get the hats?
- Where do you get the hats?

984
01:06:41,993 --> 01:06:45,271
- Army & Navy Surplus.
- Army & Navy Surplus.

985
01:06:47,640 --> 01:06:50,361
We didn't give up.
We didn't say, ''lt didn't work.''

986
01:06:50,482 --> 01:06:54,957
We were able to build
for another demonstration on Friday,

987
01:06:55,087 --> 01:06:57,922
and on Friday
we, in fact, had our riot,

988
01:06:58,051 --> 01:06:59,769
the riot that we had planned.

989
01:07:46,823 --> 01:07:48,655
The event that I remember the most

990
01:07:48,785 --> 01:07:52,258
was when the students surged
and pushed against the police

991
01:07:52,390 --> 01:07:54,541
and pushed them back,
block after block.

992
01:07:54,671 --> 01:07:57,267
I remember thinking,
''This is like a metaphor.''

993
01:07:57,394 --> 01:08:02,074
''lf enough Americans believed the war
were wrong, we could end it.''

994
01:08:40,201 --> 01:08:45,074
We controlled the downtown area
of Oakland for most of the day,

995
01:08:45,207 --> 01:08:48,485
and the cops were outnumbered
and confused and scared.

996
01:08:48,610 --> 01:08:50,522
We shut down the induction centre.

997
01:08:50,652 --> 01:08:53,407
We did what we said we'd do,
we shut the mother down.

998
01:08:53,535 --> 01:08:56,973
I went
to the Stop The Draft Week protests.

999
01:08:57,100 --> 01:08:59,376
And what I saw there
made me convinced

1000
01:08:59,501 --> 01:09:02,301
that action in the streets
of that sort

1001
01:09:02,425 --> 01:09:06,626
was not going to lead to the kind
of change necessary to stop the war.

1002
01:09:06,750 --> 01:09:10,223
I saw a lot of people from Berkeley
tear people's fences down.

1003
01:09:10,354 --> 01:09:14,032
Fences that belonged to people
that probably made $5,000 a year

1004
01:09:14,157 --> 01:09:16,832
were ripped out
to block people's cars.

1005
01:09:16,961 --> 01:09:21,675
Bobby Avakian, son of a judge,
a well-known young would-be radical,

1006
01:09:21,806 --> 01:09:24,880
let the air out of the tyres
of the district attorney.

1007
01:09:25,010 --> 01:09:26,728
This was going to stop the war?

1008
01:09:26,851 --> 01:09:32,249
I just thought this was a burlesque
of opposition to the war.

1009
01:09:32,377 --> 01:09:34,175
There's nothing else to do.

1010
01:09:34,300 --> 01:09:36,861
The picketing and all of that
wasn't working.

1011
01:09:36,983 --> 01:09:38,815
lt's time for confrontation.

1012
01:09:38,945 --> 01:09:41,301
We did stumble upon a strategy
where we said,

1013
01:09:41,427 --> 01:09:44,501
''lf you continue that war in Vietnam,

1014
01:09:44,631 --> 01:09:48,263
there's going to be chaos here
in the streets of the United States.''

1015
01:09:48,395 --> 01:09:51,628
''Every place you try
to do anything to do with the war,

1016
01:09:51,759 --> 01:09:55,037
there's going to be
thousands of young people rioting,

1017
01:09:55,162 --> 01:09:56,960
trying to stop you from doing it.''

1018
01:09:57,084 --> 01:09:59,553
While it was a great success
a turning point,

1019
01:09:59,687 --> 01:10:02,077
it was also
the first clear demonstration

1020
01:10:02,210 --> 01:10:06,491
that the radical part
of the anti-Vietnam War movement

1021
01:10:06,614 --> 01:10:09,733
was coming up
against its own limitations.

1022
01:10:09,858 --> 01:10:14,731
It didn't really have the weight
in society to stop the war.

1023
01:10:14,864 --> 01:10:17,140
I think that it was after that

1024
01:10:17,266 --> 01:10:18,984
that the Berkeley radical scene

1025
01:10:19,108 --> 01:10:21,577
became more and more
cut off from reality,

1026
01:10:21,711 --> 01:10:24,386
and the question
of moving American society,

1027
01:10:24,514 --> 01:10:28,430
changing people,
really was getting lost.

1028
01:10:28,558 --> 01:10:31,472
- Move. l've got to go to work.
- There's a war on.

1029
01:10:31,602 --> 01:10:33,559
I don't care. l've got to go to work.

1030
01:10:39,290 --> 01:10:46,328
We began to see ourselves as,
you know, glue in the keyholes.

1031
01:10:46,457 --> 01:10:50,339
We began to see ourselves
as obstacles

1032
01:10:50,462 --> 01:10:57,021
in the way of the system
fulfilling its potential

1033
01:10:57,150 --> 01:11:00,303
for wreaking destruction
all over the world.

1034
01:11:00,432 --> 01:11:03,631
I think we began to see ourselves

1035
01:11:03,756 --> 01:11:08,231
as being as big a pain in the butt
as we could,

1036
01:11:08,362 --> 01:11:13,360
and I think we lost the idea
that we could be victorious.

1037
01:11:13,487 --> 01:11:18,167
As confrontation and sit-in
and street demonstrations escalated,

1038
01:11:18,292 --> 01:11:22,573
the rest of the United States'
political community was left behind.

1039
01:11:22,697 --> 01:11:26,978
I was interested in the rest of the
United States, in the Newport Beach.

1040
01:11:27,101 --> 01:11:28,979
Those people l'd failed with

1041
01:11:29,104 --> 01:11:31,825
in the Thanksgiving vacation
Free Speech Movement

1042
01:11:31,947 --> 01:11:35,420
were the people you had to reach
if you were going to stop the war,

1043
01:11:35,551 --> 01:11:38,829
and the way to do that was not
to go down and sit in in the streets

1044
01:11:38,954 --> 01:11:41,344
in front of
the Oakland Draft lnduction Center

1045
01:11:41,477 --> 01:11:43,514
and tear up fences
and block streets.

1046
01:11:43,639 --> 01:11:46,439
The way to do that
was to be active electorally.

1047
01:11:46,563 --> 01:11:50,115
After the Tet Offensive,
when Westmoreland came to Johnson,

1048
01:11:50,247 --> 01:11:53,639
and said, ''ln order to continue
the land war in Vietnam,

1049
01:11:53,770 --> 01:11:56,445
we're going to need a million men,''

1050
01:11:56,573 --> 01:11:59,931
Johnson was told by J Edgar Hoover

1051
01:12:00,057 --> 01:12:04,133
that if we tried to get a million men
out of this country,

1052
01:12:04,261 --> 01:12:08,337
he could not ensure
the domestic security of this country.

1053
01:12:08,466 --> 01:12:12,462
And that was one of the questions,
one of the considerations he made,

1054
01:12:12,591 --> 01:12:14,822
when he decided to end the land war,

1055
01:12:14,954 --> 01:12:18,632
to begin to pull back
from the land war, and to resign

1056
01:12:18,757 --> 01:12:21,432
as an expression
of the failure of his policy

1057
01:12:21,560 --> 01:12:23,916
to win the war in Vietnam.

1058
01:12:24,043 --> 01:12:29,121
And Hoover saying
that he couldn't protect,

1059
01:12:29,249 --> 01:12:32,722
he couldn't ensure domestic security,
was a truthful statement

1060
01:12:32,852 --> 01:12:35,732
about the power
of the anti-war movement at that time.

1061
01:12:35,856 --> 01:12:39,534
We did put limits on America's
ability to wage the war in Vietnam.

1062
01:12:41,983 --> 01:12:45,182
I shall not seek

1063
01:12:45,306 --> 01:12:47,775
and I will not accept

1064
01:12:47,909 --> 01:12:52,350
the nomination of my party
for another term as your president.

1065
01:12:53,235 --> 01:12:55,831
We want to talk about this thing
called violence

1066
01:12:55,958 --> 01:12:57,915
that everybody is so afraid about.

1067
01:12:58,040 --> 01:13:00,954
Here you are, talking about
you're afraid of violence,

1068
01:13:01,083 --> 01:13:05,603
and the honky drafted you
out of school to go fight in Vietnam.

1069
01:13:05,729 --> 01:13:09,930
You sit in front of your TV sets
and listen to LBJ tell you

1070
01:13:10,053 --> 01:13:15,451
that violence never accomplishes
anything, my fellow Americans.

1071
01:13:16,340 --> 01:13:19,778
You ought to tell him clear,
''lf you don't want any trouble,

1072
01:13:19,904 --> 01:13:23,377
keep your filthy white hands
off our beautiful black skin.''

1073
01:13:23,507 --> 01:13:25,897
Keep them off. Keep them off.

1074
01:13:42,969 --> 01:13:46,647
In the streets of Oakland,
a few miles from the Berkeley campus,

1075
01:13:46,773 --> 01:13:50,815
the Black Panthers came forward
as the cutting edge of Black Power.

1076
01:13:50,937 --> 01:13:54,819
Their militancy had a magnetic effect
on the student movement.

1077
01:13:54,942 --> 01:13:58,175
We want the Panthers to be our friends.

1078
01:13:58,305 --> 01:14:01,538
We want to follow their lead

1079
01:14:01,669 --> 01:14:05,221
in some fashion that's confusing,
that's mysterious.

1080
01:14:05,353 --> 01:14:08,631
All we are aware of, we want to go,
black and white together,

1081
01:14:08,757 --> 01:14:11,796
into some positive future
against the oppressor

1082
01:14:11,920 --> 01:14:14,071
who was feeling ever more oppressive.

1083
01:14:14,203 --> 01:14:17,881
Bobby Seale and Huey Newton
formed the Black Panther Party

1084
01:14:18,006 --> 01:14:19,678
in the fall of '66.

1085
01:14:19,808 --> 01:14:21,845
They drew up a ten-point platform

1086
01:14:21,971 --> 01:14:25,489
addressing community needs
from education to housing.

1087
01:14:25,615 --> 01:14:27,891
The most pressing issue
was police violence

1088
01:14:28,018 --> 01:14:29,896
against Oakland's black community.

1089
01:14:30,019 --> 01:14:33,537
The Panthers decided to arm
themselves and patrol the police.

1090
01:14:33,663 --> 01:14:36,737
People might imagine
we were right behind the police car.

1091
01:14:36,867 --> 01:14:39,827
No. We may be four blocks away.
We just drive through.

1092
01:14:39,951 --> 01:14:43,070
If we see the police arrest somebody,
we'd get out of the car

1093
01:14:43,193 --> 01:14:45,389
with our guns, tape recorders,
law books.

1094
01:14:45,516 --> 01:14:48,669
By now, we have six, seven members
doing this, all with guns.

1095
01:14:48,800 --> 01:14:52,078
How we got our guns
was fantastic, too, the first guns.

1096
01:14:52,204 --> 01:14:56,086
The Little Red Book, The Thoughts
Of Chairman Mao Tse-Tung.

1097
01:14:56,207 --> 01:15:00,089
Huey calls me and says, ''l know how
we can raise some money for guns.''

1098
01:15:00,212 --> 01:15:03,890
I said, ''How?'' He said, ''The Little
Red Book. lt's all over the news.''

1099
01:15:04,017 --> 01:15:07,295
''l heard you can buy them
at the China bookstore in Frisco.''

1100
01:15:07,420 --> 01:15:10,141
''How much money have you got?''
I said, ''50 bucks.''

1101
01:15:10,263 --> 01:15:13,337
We run to the China bookstore,
buy about 1 00 of these books.

1102
01:15:13,466 --> 01:15:15,935
We got our guns strapped on our side.
I got a .45,

1103
01:15:16,069 --> 01:15:18,904
Huey's holding a shotgun,
Little Bobby's got a Carbine.

1104
01:15:19,033 --> 01:15:22,072
We got these bags over our shoulders
with Little Red Books.

1105
01:15:22,196 --> 01:15:25,908
''Red Books! $1 !'' We were buying them
for 20 cents and selling them for $1 ,

1106
01:15:26,040 --> 01:15:29,318
Berkeley Campus,
at Sather Gate right there!

1107
01:15:29,444 --> 01:15:31,675
We sold out in the matter of an hour.

1108
01:15:31,807 --> 01:15:34,881
We took this 1 00 bucks
and we'd buy some more Red Books.

1109
01:15:35,009 --> 01:15:38,482
We made $200, $300. We went out
and bought two shotguns that day

1110
01:15:38,614 --> 01:15:41,892
with The Little Red Book!
We hadn't even read the thing.

1111
01:15:42,018 --> 01:15:46,094
People think we came up with this
hardcore ideology related to Mao...

1112
01:15:46,222 --> 01:15:48,532
We must have sold the book
two or three months

1113
01:15:48,664 --> 01:15:51,817
before we decided to open the thing
and actually read it.

1114
01:15:51,948 --> 01:15:55,864
Anyway, the next thing I know,
l'm marching on the Capitol.

1115
01:15:55,993 --> 01:15:59,511
Because we were up there to protest
a bill they were trying to put in

1116
01:15:59,637 --> 01:16:01,309
to keep us from carrying guns.

1117
01:16:01,438 --> 01:16:04,113
Ronald Reagan is over here
on the big front lawn.

1118
01:16:04,241 --> 01:16:06,073
I got a statement to read.

1119
01:16:06,204 --> 01:16:10,325
The Black Panther Party calls upon
American people in general

1120
01:16:10,448 --> 01:16:12,201
and the black people in particular

1121
01:16:12,331 --> 01:16:16,088
to take note
of the racist California legislature,

1122
01:16:16,214 --> 01:16:18,126
which is considering legislation

1123
01:16:18,256 --> 01:16:21,136
aimed at keeping black people
disarmed and powerless

1124
01:16:21,260 --> 01:16:24,938
at the very same time racist police
agencies throughout the country

1125
01:16:25,064 --> 01:16:30,017
are intensifying the terror, brutality,
murder and repression of black people.

1126
01:16:30,149 --> 01:16:34,590
Ronald Reagan is escorted off the lawn
by the state capitol police.

1127
01:16:34,715 --> 01:16:38,427
I said, ''We can go inside somewhere.
lsn't there a spectator section?''

1128
01:16:38,559 --> 01:16:43,591
I have these Black Panthers up here.

1129
01:16:43,724 --> 01:16:44,713
Can we get in here?

1130
01:16:44,845 --> 01:16:47,919
- Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
- Are you going to arrest him?

1131
01:16:48,049 --> 01:16:51,840
- Am I under arrest?
- Did you place him under arrest?

1132
01:16:51,974 --> 01:16:55,765
Am I under arrest? Take your hands
off me if l'm not under arrest.

1133
01:16:55,897 --> 01:16:59,289
- Am I under arrest?
- Take your hands off me!

1134
01:16:59,421 --> 01:17:02,939
They've put trumped-up charges
of conspiracy and felonies

1135
01:17:03,065 --> 01:17:06,343
on everyone who went in
to exercise a constitutional right

1136
01:17:06,469 --> 01:17:09,827
and said they had no right
to bear arms in a public place.

1137
01:17:09,952 --> 01:17:14,073
The California penal code,
section 1 2020 through 1 2027,

1138
01:17:14,197 --> 01:17:16,666
and the Second Amendment
of the Constitution

1139
01:17:16,800 --> 01:17:21,639
guarantees the citizen a right
to bear arms on public property.

1140
01:17:21,765 --> 01:17:26,604
Our organisation was like a social
evolutionary accident, so to speak.

1141
01:17:26,731 --> 01:17:30,009
When you compare
the NAACP from 1 908

1142
01:17:30,135 --> 01:17:32,776
and other organisations, etc,

1143
01:17:32,897 --> 01:17:36,370
and all the years they put in
to become established,

1144
01:17:36,501 --> 01:17:41,021
in just six months the Black Panther
Party has international notoriety.

1145
01:17:41,146 --> 01:17:45,461
We're on the front page of the London
Times and papers in Africa somewhere.

1146
01:17:45,592 --> 01:17:48,950
We were a broke little organisation
with a number of shotguns,

1147
01:17:49,075 --> 01:17:52,627
a very weak treasury, and we were
worried about how to pay the rent.

1148
01:17:52,759 --> 01:17:56,037
And, boom.
I mean, we were shocking people.

1149
01:17:56,163 --> 01:18:00,045
We have probably said
to white America...

1150
01:18:00,167 --> 01:18:03,845
The people who were observing us
when we came out with the guns

1151
01:18:03,971 --> 01:18:06,247
are saying, ''Niggers with guns!''

1152
01:18:06,374 --> 01:18:09,652
lt's like a fear.
They don't even have to say it.

1153
01:18:09,778 --> 01:18:13,251
Their faces said it.
''There's too many niggers with guns.''

1154
01:18:13,381 --> 01:18:15,452
Like they know
that they repressed us,

1155
01:18:15,583 --> 01:18:19,261
and now we were organised with guns.
This is the new step.

1156
01:18:19,388 --> 01:18:23,225
lt's symbolic that, ''They're not
going to be non-violent any more.''

1157
01:18:29,358 --> 01:18:32,636
On the night of October 28th 1 967,

1158
01:18:32,762 --> 01:18:36,553
Huey Newton was stopped by police.
There was gunfire.

1159
01:18:36,687 --> 01:18:40,478
Officer Fry was killed, and Huey
Newton was arrested for murder.

1160
01:18:40,610 --> 01:18:42,966
His trial drew the student movement

1161
01:18:43,093 --> 01:18:45,768
into an alliance
with the Black Panthers.

1162
01:18:45,896 --> 01:18:49,653
''Free Huey'' became our rallying cry.

1163
01:18:49,781 --> 01:18:52,057
The organisation just propelled.

1164
01:18:52,183 --> 01:18:56,942
It took off like a prairie fire,
it spread everywhere.

1165
01:18:57,068 --> 01:18:59,344
Certainly beyond my imagination.

1166
01:18:59,471 --> 01:19:02,351
After Huey's arrest,

1167
01:19:02,475 --> 01:19:05,150
that's when things
really started rolling.

1168
01:19:05,277 --> 01:19:07,952
Free Huey now or else!
Free Huey now or else!

1169
01:19:19,773 --> 01:19:23,246
The Panthers
exercised a heavy influence

1170
01:19:23,377 --> 01:19:26,257
in the imagination of the white left,

1171
01:19:26,380 --> 01:19:30,661
partly because the white left
was confused about who it was

1172
01:19:30,785 --> 01:19:33,061
and what it ought to do.

1173
01:19:33,187 --> 01:19:35,862
They were fascinated
by this tough, macho image

1174
01:19:35,990 --> 01:19:40,863
and they followed it not so much
wilfully but involuntarily,

1175
01:19:40,996 --> 01:19:44,878
because it was a projection out there
of the thing in their own actions

1176
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:46,672
that thrilled them most.

1177
01:19:46,802 --> 01:19:50,275
We had captured the imagination
of the white radical left

1178
01:19:50,406 --> 01:19:53,879
to a point
that its whole identification

1179
01:19:54,010 --> 01:19:57,688
became connected with what
the Black Panther Party was doing,

1180
01:19:57,814 --> 01:20:00,090
how it was personifying things.

1181
01:20:00,217 --> 01:20:02,573
And it was like we influenced them

1182
01:20:02,699 --> 01:20:06,251
in whatever direction
we thought that they should go.

1183
01:20:06,384 --> 01:20:11,542
I don't like to say suck up,
but they were awed by the Panthers.

1184
01:20:11,669 --> 01:20:15,631
The Panthers were somehow
confronting the white power structure

1185
01:20:15,754 --> 01:20:18,828
the way they would have liked
to have done, some of them.

1186
01:20:18,957 --> 01:20:22,430
But not all. Many of the whites
who led the Stop The Draft Week

1187
01:20:22,561 --> 01:20:24,439
could have been involved with it.

1188
01:20:24,563 --> 01:20:27,841
Many of those people who had been
in some parts of the early SDS

1189
01:20:27,967 --> 01:20:29,446
was as sceptical as I was.

1190
01:20:29,569 --> 01:20:33,247
But no one would, of course,
say any of these remarks publicly.

1191
01:20:33,373 --> 01:20:36,253
I mean, you didn't need that hassle.

1192
01:20:36,376 --> 01:20:38,572
So, what a lot of us did,

1193
01:20:38,698 --> 01:20:41,976
I think to the detriment
of the black movement, perhaps,

1194
01:20:42,102 --> 01:20:43,980
and to the left movement in general,

1195
01:20:44,104 --> 01:20:46,665
a lot of us with years
of political experience

1196
01:20:46,787 --> 01:20:49,018
and organisational skills
dropped out.

1197
01:20:49,150 --> 01:20:52,110
If not dropped out,
stepped to the side in this period.

1198
01:20:52,233 --> 01:20:52,472
Huey P Newton is the only leader
that black people should recognise!

1199
01:20:52,473 --> 01:20:56,355
Huey P Newton is the only leader
that black people should recognise!

1200
01:20:56,478 --> 01:21:01,237
A man who is willing to stand up
and face that pig,

1201
01:21:01,363 --> 01:21:03,241
and on his own terms.

1202
01:21:03,366 --> 01:21:05,801
Gun for gun if necessary.

1203
01:21:05,928 --> 01:21:08,238
This must be done!

1204
01:21:08,370 --> 01:21:10,008
You cannot sit there

1205
01:21:10,132 --> 01:21:14,014
and allow that man
to be railroaded any more.

1206
01:21:14,137 --> 01:21:20,537
You must free our leader. He must
be freed, and he will be freed.

1207
01:21:20,664 --> 01:21:24,342
Two days after the assassination
of Martin Luther King,

1208
01:21:24,468 --> 01:21:28,146
the war of nerves between the
Black Panthers and the Oakland police

1209
01:21:28,273 --> 01:21:29,308
came to a climax.

1210
01:21:29,434 --> 01:21:32,189
On April 6th 1 968,

1211
01:21:32,316 --> 01:21:35,549
a shoot-out erupted
in which Eldridge Cleaver was wounded

1212
01:21:35,680 --> 01:21:37,717
and Bobby Hutton was killed.

1213
01:21:37,843 --> 01:21:40,837
Bobby Hutton
was instructed by the cops

1214
01:21:40,966 --> 01:21:46,841
to run from here to the police car,
or the area where it was,

1215
01:21:46,972 --> 01:21:50,171
and was literally shot down.

1216
01:21:50,296 --> 01:21:52,572
He was shot over ten times.

1217
01:21:52,699 --> 01:21:56,581
He had five pistol bullets
in his head.

1218
01:21:56,702 --> 01:21:59,012
A clear-cut case of murder.

1219
01:21:59,145 --> 01:22:00,977
As brother Huey P Newton says,

1220
01:22:01,108 --> 01:22:04,466
racist pig cops must stop
their wanton murder and brutality

1221
01:22:04,592 --> 01:22:06,743
or suffer the wrath
of armed black people

1222
01:22:06,874 --> 01:22:09,595
and the black communities
defending themselves.

1223
01:22:09,717 --> 01:22:12,517
Historically, in retrospect,

1224
01:22:12,640 --> 01:22:17,924
those guns
were somewhat our nemesis.

1225
01:22:18,046 --> 01:22:21,803
We were never really able
to play that down.

1226
01:22:21,931 --> 01:22:23,763
The police, the media, used that.

1227
01:22:23,892 --> 01:22:29,130
We got hung up into a confrontational
thing with the police over those guns

1228
01:22:29,258 --> 01:22:32,093
that we were never really able
to live down.

1229
01:22:32,222 --> 01:22:35,261
We say, bring it on.
If you want war, let there be war.

1230
01:22:35,385 --> 01:22:37,183
This is what we say. ls that clear?

1231
01:22:37,306 --> 01:22:40,425
In other words, if he is convicted
and sentenced to death,

1232
01:22:40,550 --> 01:22:41,949
Oakland will erupt.

1233
01:22:42,072 --> 01:22:45,750
This whole country will erupt.
We're going to do everything we can

1234
01:22:45,876 --> 01:22:49,554
to see to it that the whole world
erupts. ls that clear?

1235
01:22:49,680 --> 01:22:53,278
The Panthers
seemed even crazier than they were

1236
01:22:53,404 --> 01:22:56,956
because they were playing the media
and the media was loving them.

1237
01:22:57,088 --> 01:22:59,045
The media picked up their current,

1238
01:22:59,171 --> 01:23:01,892
fed the narrowest parts
of their image back to us

1239
01:23:02,013 --> 01:23:04,289
in the most dramatic, hyped terms,

1240
01:23:04,416 --> 01:23:07,889
that the Panthers themselves
wanted them to be projected.

1241
01:23:08,020 --> 01:23:09,453
It drove the police crazy.

1242
01:23:09,582 --> 01:23:13,260
They were furious and wanted
to get them all over the country,

1243
01:23:13,386 --> 01:23:15,537
and it drove some of us...

1244
01:23:15,668 --> 01:23:20,507
Well, it incited some of us
with superficial fantasies

1245
01:23:20,634 --> 01:23:25,314
of a kind of revolution
that was completely inappropriate.

1246
01:23:25,439 --> 01:23:29,117
It had nothing to do with
the actual landscape of possibility.

1247
01:23:29,243 --> 01:23:33,718
It was interesting to me
more deeply and metaphorically.

1248
01:23:33,848 --> 01:23:36,204
If that was what they were doing,

1249
01:23:36,331 --> 01:23:39,370
what was appropriate
in our community?

1250
01:23:39,494 --> 01:23:42,967
The Panthers, in a sense,
let, in my opinion,

1251
01:23:43,098 --> 01:23:44,976
white radicals off the hook,

1252
01:23:45,100 --> 01:23:48,458
some white radicals, not all,
some white radicals off the hook

1253
01:23:48,584 --> 01:23:51,896
for what SNCC had challenged them
about three years earlier.

1254
01:23:52,028 --> 01:23:54,463
That was to organise
the white community.

1255
01:23:54,590 --> 01:23:58,791
They could say they supported the
Panthers as they were the vanguard.

1256
01:23:58,915 --> 01:24:01,989
They assumed the movement
could only be led by blacks.

1257
01:24:02,119 --> 01:24:06,400
They made it clear blacks would be
the group to start the revolution,

1258
01:24:06,524 --> 01:24:10,076
and that the Panthers were the army
of that black vanguard.

1259
01:25:12,115 --> 01:25:14,676
I was taken up with,

1260
01:25:14,797 --> 01:25:17,438
''Now we're not only
a protest movement,

1261
01:25:17,560 --> 01:25:20,440
we're not only a movement
to end the war in Vietnam,

1262
01:25:20,564 --> 01:25:23,364
but we are a revolutionary movement.''

1263
01:25:23,487 --> 01:25:26,925
We were wrong.
It wasn't a revolutionary situation.

1264
01:25:27,050 --> 01:25:29,201
But it was a mistake.

1265
01:25:30,814 --> 01:25:33,170
Everybody can make a few mistakes.

1266
01:25:33,297 --> 01:25:37,179
And, at the time,
it had a lot of the aspects to us

1267
01:25:37,302 --> 01:25:39,100
of a revolutionary situation.

1268
01:25:39,224 --> 01:25:42,298
'68 was a real high time,
what we were doing.

1269
01:25:42,427 --> 01:25:45,307
We identified
with the student movement

1270
01:25:45,430 --> 01:25:47,740
and the large protest movement
in Paris.

1271
01:25:47,873 --> 01:25:49,545
There was the Prague Spring

1272
01:25:49,675 --> 01:25:53,353
and the feeling that revolution
was in the air, east and west,

1273
01:25:53,479 --> 01:25:55,471
capitalist and communist.

1274
01:25:55,601 --> 01:25:58,070
It was all coming apart
in a new spirit.

1275
01:25:58,204 --> 01:26:00,355
A new wave of liberation
was in the air.

1276
01:26:00,487 --> 01:26:04,039
I felt that the world was unravelling,
history had speeded up,

1277
01:26:04,171 --> 01:26:06,846
that the world
was swirling around me.

1278
01:26:06,973 --> 01:26:10,855
The movement had expanded.
The anti-war movement was immense.

1279
01:26:10,978 --> 01:26:13,733
The women's liberation movement
had begun.

1280
01:26:13,861 --> 01:26:18,381
The world was undergoing change at
a rate that I could hardly comprehend,

1281
01:26:18,507 --> 01:26:22,423
and yet I was in it and I was
part of it, and I was changing.

1282
01:26:28,197 --> 01:26:32,273
I always remember
this particular period of time,

1283
01:26:32,402 --> 01:26:35,396
because the change
was so phenomenal.

1284
01:26:35,524 --> 01:26:36,843
I went to sleep one night

1285
01:26:36,966 --> 01:26:40,119
and I was a woman
who was dissatisfied

1286
01:26:40,250 --> 01:26:42,606
with my position
as a woman in society,

1287
01:26:42,733 --> 01:26:45,613
but I felt solitary
in that dissatisfaction.

1288
01:26:45,735 --> 01:26:49,811
And suddenly I wake up
and, right and left,

1289
01:26:49,940 --> 01:26:52,501
everybody is speaking about it.

1290
01:26:52,623 --> 01:26:56,938
I have women
who agree with me everywhere.

1291
01:26:57,068 --> 01:26:59,139
We start to form a sisterhood.

1292
01:26:59,270 --> 01:27:02,743
Everything in my life that has
disturbed me is being challenged.

1293
01:27:02,874 --> 01:27:07,155
Things that haven't disturbed me
before, suddenly they do.

1294
01:27:07,279 --> 01:27:12,038
When we began
to try to take a more active role

1295
01:27:12,164 --> 01:27:16,844
in steering committees
and decision-making forums

1296
01:27:16,969 --> 01:27:18,847
in the movement,

1297
01:27:18,972 --> 01:27:24,529
we began to see our comrades
resisting our input.

1298
01:27:24,658 --> 01:27:29,213
And we looked at them
and we said, ''What?''

1299
01:27:29,343 --> 01:27:33,544
''How can they do this to us?
These are our brothers.''

1300
01:27:33,668 --> 01:27:36,742
''Why aren't they interested
in what we have to say?''

1301
01:27:36,871 --> 01:27:42,348
''They're only interested in the fact
that we're always there for them.''

1302
01:27:42,477 --> 01:27:45,950
''And we always make the coffee
and we run off the leaflets

1303
01:27:46,081 --> 01:27:50,157
and we make all the telephone calls
late into the night,

1304
01:27:50,286 --> 01:27:53,964
and yet when we try to participate
on a more active level,

1305
01:27:54,089 --> 01:27:56,810
we meet resistance.''

1306
01:27:56,933 --> 01:27:59,323
What you see here
is the beginning of a movement

1307
01:27:59,456 --> 01:28:02,530
that women are human beings
and that we have equal rights.

1308
01:28:02,659 --> 01:28:06,337
We intend to go to school and have
childcare so we can go to school.

1309
01:28:06,463 --> 01:28:10,698
We want the university to run classes
that teach us about our history,

1310
01:28:10,828 --> 01:28:14,106
the same as black people
want to learn about their history.

1311
01:28:14,232 --> 01:28:17,465
That's what is happening today.
This is just the beginning.

1312
01:28:17,596 --> 01:28:19,633
One of the ways the women's movement

1313
01:28:19,757 --> 01:28:24,038
is the logical and maybe even
inevitable conclusion of the '60s

1314
01:28:24,162 --> 01:28:27,042
is that throughout the '60s
we were trying to imagine

1315
01:28:27,166 --> 01:28:30,046
how to live differently,
how to change the world.

1316
01:28:30,169 --> 01:28:33,642
The women's movement took much
from the civil-rights movement,

1317
01:28:33,772 --> 01:28:38,566
the new left, the anti-war movement,
but we brought it home.

1318
01:28:38,698 --> 01:28:42,171
We brought it into the kitchen,
we brought it into the bedroom,

1319
01:28:42,302 --> 01:28:46,982
we brought it into the most personal,
intimate aspects of people's lives.

1320
01:28:47,107 --> 01:28:49,064
It was hard to deny there.

1321
01:28:49,189 --> 01:28:51,910
It was hard to ignore those issues.

1322
01:28:52,032 --> 01:28:54,149
When I thought of revolution then,

1323
01:28:54,275 --> 01:28:59,399
the whole idea had assumed
complex, enormous dimensions.

1324
01:28:59,520 --> 01:29:03,198
It didn't mean a simple change
in the institutional order.

1325
01:29:03,324 --> 01:29:08,004
It meant a coordinated change
in all the dimensions,

1326
01:29:08,130 --> 01:29:09,802
all the aspects of life.

1327
01:29:09,932 --> 01:29:12,971
How we were with ourselves,
how we were with each other.

1328
01:29:13,095 --> 01:29:16,328
This was so complex a programme,
you couldn't write it down

1329
01:29:16,459 --> 01:29:20,091
as the 1 3-point programme
of the Berkeley Revolutionary Front.

1330
01:29:20,223 --> 01:29:24,538
This was something that would take
thousands, millions of people

1331
01:29:24,667 --> 01:29:28,345
engaged all their lives in exploring
this end of it and this end of it

1332
01:29:28,472 --> 01:29:30,668
and how these ends
might fit together,

1333
01:29:30,794 --> 01:29:32,865
and it was clear by then

1334
01:29:32,997 --> 01:29:35,672
that all this exploration
was there to do.

1335
01:29:35,800 --> 01:29:39,273
People had begun
each part of the exploration.

1336
01:29:39,403 --> 01:29:41,679
I forbear to list them, OK?

1337
01:29:41,806 --> 01:29:46,281
And, at the same time, it seemed
impossible. There was no time.

1338
01:29:46,411 --> 01:29:50,293
The war got worse faster,
the political activity got worse faster,

1339
01:29:50,415 --> 01:29:52,611
they were killing
more and more people.

1340
01:29:52,738 --> 01:29:56,780
Every time you placed some degree
of hope in a national leader...

1341
01:29:58,905 --> 01:30:01,181
So much life, so much death.

1342
01:30:01,308 --> 01:30:05,065
So much possibility,
so much impossibility.

1343
01:30:06,072 --> 01:30:12,027
There we were,
attempting to change national politics,

1344
01:30:12,159 --> 01:30:15,233
and found ourselves
at the Chicago Convention.

1345
01:30:15,363 --> 01:30:20,236
It changed American politics
in unpredictable ways.

1346
01:30:21,449 --> 01:30:24,363
We had not anticipated,

1347
01:30:24,492 --> 01:30:28,613
speaking for those involved
in the electoral side of politics,

1348
01:30:28,737 --> 01:30:34,533
we did not anticipate
the arbitrary exercise of authority

1349
01:30:34,663 --> 01:30:37,543
that Mayor Daley
would bring to bear in Chicago.

1350
01:30:37,667 --> 01:30:39,066
And it was phenomenal.

1351
01:30:39,189 --> 01:30:39,668
Mr Chairman,
most delegates to this convention

1352
01:30:39,669 --> 01:30:42,663
Mr Chairman,
most delegates to this convention

1353
01:30:42,792 --> 01:30:47,073
do not know that thousands
of young people are being beaten

1354
01:30:47,197 --> 01:30:49,632
in the streets of Chicago.

1355
01:30:53,885 --> 01:30:57,163
And for that reason
and that reason alone,

1356
01:30:57,287 --> 01:31:01,442
I request the suspension of the rules
for the purpose of adjournment

1357
01:31:01,572 --> 01:31:05,853
for two weeks to relocate
the convention in another city

1358
01:31:05,978 --> 01:31:08,858
of the choosing
of the Democratic National Committee

1359
01:31:08,980 --> 01:31:10,937
and the presidential candidates...

1360
01:31:11,062 --> 01:31:14,819
Wisconsin is not recognised
for that purpose!

1361
01:31:14,947 --> 01:31:19,820
There was a side of American politics
that was vicious and violent,

1362
01:31:19,953 --> 01:31:22,024
and that's what we saw in Chicago.

1363
01:31:22,154 --> 01:31:24,829
Daley rolled over
the anti-war forces,

1364
01:31:24,958 --> 01:31:29,990
and it was a destruction
of the Democratic Party.

1365
01:31:30,123 --> 01:31:33,641
It seemed impossible

1366
01:31:33,768 --> 01:31:39,052
that there could be any significant
electoral path toward ending the war

1367
01:31:39,173 --> 01:31:41,244
following the convention.

1368
01:31:41,376 --> 01:31:44,849
It seemed that what had happened
in the parks of Chicago

1369
01:31:44,980 --> 01:31:49,101
made the anti-war movement
destined for direct action

1370
01:31:49,224 --> 01:31:51,614
for quite a period of time.

1371
01:31:51,747 --> 01:31:53,864
The violence in Chicago

1372
01:31:53,989 --> 01:31:57,507
triggered confrontations on campuses
across the country.

1373
01:31:57,633 --> 01:32:01,788
Berkeley students calling for
a Third World College initiated a strike

1374
01:32:01,917 --> 01:32:05,390
which provoked daily battles
between police and protestors.

1375
01:32:05,521 --> 01:32:09,199
After eight weeks, Governor Reagan
sent in the National Guard

1376
01:32:09,326 --> 01:32:11,204
and the strike died down.

1377
01:32:11,328 --> 01:32:14,640
Eventually, an ethnic studies programme
was established,

1378
01:32:14,772 --> 01:32:18,529
but in the wake of the strike,
an atmosphere of tension remained.

1379
01:32:18,656 --> 01:32:21,650
A month later,
student and community activists

1380
01:32:21,779 --> 01:32:24,534
came together
to create People's Park.

1381
01:32:55,976 --> 01:33:00,018
I was one of those people
who believed that the counterculture

1382
01:33:00,141 --> 01:33:02,702
could be revolutionary.

1383
01:33:04,906 --> 01:33:08,584
lt's hard to talk about that
without talking about People's Park.

1384
01:33:08,710 --> 01:33:12,592
A group of people
took some corporate land

1385
01:33:12,714 --> 01:33:17,394
owned by the University of California
that was a parking lot,

1386
01:33:17,520 --> 01:33:19,192
turned it into a park

1387
01:33:19,322 --> 01:33:23,000
and then said, ''We're using the land
better than you used it,

1388
01:33:23,125 --> 01:33:25,960
and it's ours.''

1389
01:33:26,089 --> 01:33:29,322
For a brief moment in history,
in People's Park,

1390
01:33:29,453 --> 01:33:33,131
the counterculture
and political activists

1391
01:33:33,257 --> 01:33:35,135
had a magical fusion.

1392
01:33:36,220 --> 01:33:39,738
It was a way of looking
at the future. lt was utopian.

1393
01:33:39,864 --> 01:33:44,737
It was a way of saying,
''lf we had control of our lives,

1394
01:33:44,870 --> 01:33:47,260
this is what it would look like.''

1395
01:34:05,451 --> 01:34:08,126
In a down-to-earth way,

1396
01:34:08,255 --> 01:34:13,732
we were showing in our very activity
the image of a new society.

1397
01:34:13,860 --> 01:34:17,697
Our job is to form a counterculture,

1398
01:34:17,825 --> 01:34:22,778
a more rural culture,
a more decentralised culture,

1399
01:34:22,911 --> 01:34:25,871
to develop counter-values
of cooperation,

1400
01:34:25,994 --> 01:34:29,272
of a production for use
rather than a production for profit,

1401
01:34:29,397 --> 01:34:32,870
develop that culture in hope
that that culture would be

1402
01:34:33,001 --> 01:34:37,635
in revolutionary contradiction
to a bourgeois culture.

1403
01:34:37,767 --> 01:34:40,681
And that we should view ourselves
as revolutionaries

1404
01:34:40,809 --> 01:34:44,487
but really as founding mothers
and fathers of this counterculture.

1405
01:34:44,614 --> 01:34:46,412
I can almost convince myself now!

1406
01:34:46,536 --> 01:34:50,578
As I see it, the great hope
implicit in the People's Park

1407
01:34:50,701 --> 01:34:53,854
is that in our leisure time,
so to speak,

1408
01:34:53,984 --> 01:34:56,135
we will make the social revolution.

1409
01:34:56,266 --> 01:35:00,342
Property is not a thing
to keep men apart and at war,

1410
01:35:00,471 --> 01:35:04,752
but rather a medium by which
men can come together to play,

1411
01:35:04,876 --> 01:35:06,947
a people's park.

1412
01:35:07,078 --> 01:35:13,079
People's Park managed to focus
all of the frustrations

1413
01:35:13,205 --> 01:35:17,406
as well as some of the ideals
of the '60s.

1414
01:35:17,530 --> 01:35:19,806
There was a belief
in the environment,

1415
01:35:19,932 --> 01:35:22,732
a belief in the participation
of ordinary people

1416
01:35:22,855 --> 01:35:24,527
in political decision-making,

1417
01:35:24,657 --> 01:35:27,332
a belief that a lot of things
ought to count

1418
01:35:27,460 --> 01:35:29,178
that traditionally don't count

1419
01:35:29,302 --> 01:35:33,218
when they're caught up in government
and university bureaucracy.

1420
01:35:33,346 --> 01:35:34,495
There was all of that.

1421
01:35:34,628 --> 01:35:38,146
But the fact remains that
I believe the People's Park incident

1422
01:35:38,272 --> 01:35:41,311
was extremely cynical
on the part of the demonstrators.

1423
01:35:41,436 --> 01:35:43,154
They wanted a confrontation.

1424
01:35:43,278 --> 01:35:48,037
What mattered was getting people
out in the streets, demonstrating.

1425
01:35:48,162 --> 01:35:51,840
Roger Hinds and the regents
and Ronald Reagan

1426
01:35:51,967 --> 01:35:54,243
can't allow this to go on.

1427
01:35:54,370 --> 01:35:56,966
If there's one liberated territory,

1428
01:35:57,093 --> 01:36:00,850
people may get the idea there
could be other liberated territories.

1429
01:36:00,976 --> 01:36:04,733
The park issue is not the issue.

1430
01:36:04,861 --> 01:36:12,058
The issue is, ''We must have
a confrontation throughout the summer.''

1431
01:36:12,188 --> 01:36:14,623
They were
out of confrontation issues.

1432
01:36:14,751 --> 01:36:17,790
And as soon as you give them a park,

1433
01:36:17,915 --> 01:36:20,350
they'll dream up another confrontation.

1434
01:36:20,478 --> 01:36:24,190
We have been invaded by people
outside of the state,

1435
01:36:24,322 --> 01:36:28,000
outside of the cities,
we have been invaded by militants.

1436
01:36:29,127 --> 01:36:31,483
This is... We're in a revolution,

1437
01:36:31,610 --> 01:36:35,288
and the only thing, don't ever say
we're going into a revolution.

1438
01:36:35,414 --> 01:36:38,772
We're in a revolution!
Now the question is, who will win it?

1439
01:36:38,897 --> 01:36:42,688
When Jesus disrupted the foreign
recruiters, his followers said...

1440
01:36:42,822 --> 01:36:46,180
''Power to the people.
Out, demons, out.''

1441
01:36:46,306 --> 01:36:48,662
I declare this place decontaminated

1442
01:36:48,789 --> 01:36:53,070
from poisons, chains and lies,
from the abomination that defiles.

1443
01:36:53,193 --> 01:36:56,871
The demons have returned to
the nothingness from which they came.

1444
01:36:56,997 --> 01:37:00,196
Earth, water, air and fire,
witness our liberation.

1445
01:37:00,321 --> 01:37:03,554
This property is private.

1446
01:37:03,685 --> 01:37:06,360
You are now trespassing.

1447
01:37:06,487 --> 01:37:10,802
Unless you leave,
you will be arrested for trespassing.

1448
01:37:12,053 --> 01:37:16,095
If they didn't want the park, they
should've stopped us when we started,

1449
01:37:16,218 --> 01:37:19,736
and not let us work on it every day
and then just take it away.

1450
01:37:21,063 --> 01:37:23,498
lt's their park now. What can we do?

1451
01:37:24,787 --> 01:37:26,779
I have a suggestion.

1452
01:37:26,910 --> 01:37:31,065
Let's go down to the People's Park,
because we are the people!

1453
01:37:31,794 --> 01:37:35,426
We want the park! We want the park!

1454
01:38:32,501 --> 01:38:33,854
Here they come.

1455
01:39:40,574 --> 01:39:40,733
Those people told you
for days in advance

1456
01:39:40,735 --> 01:39:44,697
Those people told you
for days in advance

1457
01:39:44,818 --> 01:39:48,939
that if the university sought
to go ahead with that construction

1458
01:39:49,063 --> 01:39:53,857
on that property, they would
physically destroy the university.

1459
01:39:53,989 --> 01:39:56,630
Governor, we offered to negotiate
many times.

1460
01:39:56,751 --> 01:40:00,303
Negotiate? What is to negotiate?
What is...?

1461
01:40:00,435 --> 01:40:05,035
Wait a minute. On that issue, don't
you simply explain to these students

1462
01:40:05,161 --> 01:40:08,793
that the university has a piece
of property that it bought

1463
01:40:08,924 --> 01:40:11,120
for future construction of the campus

1464
01:40:11,247 --> 01:40:15,038
and it was now going ahead with
the plan? What do you mean, negotiate?

1465
01:40:15,172 --> 01:40:17,243
Governor Reagan, the time has passed

1466
01:40:17,374 --> 01:40:20,049
when the university
can just ride roughshod

1467
01:40:20,177 --> 01:40:23,251
over the desires of the majority
of its student body.

1468
01:40:23,380 --> 01:40:25,656
The university
is a public institution,

1469
01:40:25,783 --> 01:40:28,857
an important institution
for all of its own community

1470
01:40:28,987 --> 01:40:31,263
and for the Berkeley community
around it.

1471
01:40:31,389 --> 01:40:34,349
All of it began the first time
some of you who know better

1472
01:40:34,473 --> 01:40:36,271
and are old enough to know better

1473
01:40:36,394 --> 01:40:38,863
let young people think
that they had the right

1474
01:40:38,997 --> 01:40:40,954
to choose the laws they would obey,

1475
01:40:41,080 --> 01:40:44,553
as long as they were doing it
in the name of social protest.

1476
01:40:50,049 --> 01:40:54,125
When the fence went up, the whole
experience of People's Park changed.

1477
01:40:54,254 --> 01:40:56,929
Governor Reagan
brought in the National Guard,

1478
01:40:57,057 --> 01:40:59,128
the city was occupied for a month,

1479
01:40:59,260 --> 01:41:02,938
and what happened is, the worst
aspects of the movement emerged.

1480
01:41:03,063 --> 01:41:06,216
People did things
that were totally counterproductive.

1481
01:41:06,347 --> 01:41:10,343
They tried to provoke the National Guard
into fixing their bayonets.

1482
01:41:10,472 --> 01:41:13,147
They tried to cause skirmishes
on the campus.

1483
01:41:13,275 --> 01:41:16,155
I found it possible
to resist the feeling,

1484
01:41:16,277 --> 01:41:18,075
the collective hallucination,

1485
01:41:18,200 --> 01:41:21,478
that we were involved
in a revolutionary struggle.

1486
01:41:21,603 --> 01:41:26,237
But there was one moment when
I became immersed in that feeling.

1487
01:41:26,369 --> 01:41:29,967
There was a peaceful demonstration
on Sproul Plaza

1488
01:41:30,092 --> 01:41:33,086
denouncing the university's
overreaction to the park,

1489
01:41:33,216 --> 01:41:35,367
the police brutality
towards students,

1490
01:41:35,499 --> 01:41:38,811
the National Guard on campus,
occupying the city.

1491
01:41:38,943 --> 01:41:42,221
My boyfriend and I and a friend of mine

1492
01:41:42,346 --> 01:41:45,624
went down to the plaza
to hear the rally,

1493
01:41:45,749 --> 01:41:46,943
and as we got there,

1494
01:41:47,071 --> 01:41:50,349
we realised that the police
were letting people into the plaza

1495
01:41:50,475 --> 01:41:52,592
but they were not letting people out.

1496
01:41:52,718 --> 01:41:56,396
My friend, by that time, had already
gone through the police lines

1497
01:41:56,521 --> 01:42:00,199
and I motioned for her to come back,
and they wouldn't let her out.

1498
01:42:00,325 --> 01:42:03,923
Pigs off campus! Pigs off campus!

1499
01:42:06,813 --> 01:42:09,773
Killers off campus!
Killers off campus!

1500
01:42:09,895 --> 01:42:12,570
..requesting you all
to leave the plaza.

1501
01:42:12,699 --> 01:42:17,823
If you don't leave, you're going
to be shot in the next five minutes.

1502
01:42:17,945 --> 01:42:21,623
I started hearing
the sounds of a helicopter,

1503
01:42:21,748 --> 01:42:25,744
and it came closer and closer
and the sound got louder and louder

1504
01:42:25,873 --> 01:42:29,185
and suddenly the helicopter
swooped over the whole campus,

1505
01:42:29,317 --> 01:42:31,309
over all the students, and I thought,

1506
01:42:31,439 --> 01:42:34,000
''We're going to be shot at.
We're the Vietcong.''

1507
01:43:01,751 --> 01:43:05,269
Everybody on the outside
of the police line was running

1508
01:43:05,396 --> 01:43:07,274
to try to get away from the gas.

1509
01:43:07,398 --> 01:43:10,916
Everybody on the inside of the police
line was trying to get out.

1510
01:43:11,042 --> 01:43:14,594
And the police were beating people
as they tried to get out.

1511
01:43:14,725 --> 01:43:18,880
We went back to Kroeber Hall
and waited for my friend to show up.

1512
01:43:19,010 --> 01:43:22,892
She'd been through the mill. She had
been throwing up, it was nausea gas.

1513
01:43:23,015 --> 01:43:25,530
So we drove up to the rose garden.

1514
01:43:25,658 --> 01:43:29,939
We were standing there, looking out
across the roses and the campus,

1515
01:43:30,062 --> 01:43:34,024
and there were still helicopters
circling around.

1516
01:43:36,229 --> 01:43:39,907
She looked at me and said, ''l can't
stand this. l'm going to get out.''

1517
01:43:40,033 --> 01:43:42,913
I said, ''l think you're right.
I think it's all over.''

1518
01:43:43,036 --> 01:43:46,998
''l don't think we can stay here any
more.'' lt was a poignant moment.

1519
01:43:47,121 --> 01:43:49,636
And a year later, we were all gone.

1520
01:43:49,764 --> 01:43:51,801
We all felt very defeated.

1521
01:43:51,927 --> 01:43:56,686
It was a horrible experience
to gas students at a peaceful rally.

1522
01:43:57,532 --> 01:43:59,204
And it was one reason

1523
01:43:59,334 --> 01:44:04,412
why people began to feel that we had
to reassert what we really stood for,

1524
01:44:04,540 --> 01:44:08,695
that we really had to protest the park

1525
01:44:08,824 --> 01:44:10,975
in a dignified and peaceful way,

1526
01:44:11,107 --> 01:44:14,545
and recapture the original spirit
of the park.

1527
01:44:15,432 --> 01:44:19,189
And that led to
the Memorial Day march.

1528
01:45:15,496 --> 01:45:17,727
We'll get People's Park
back eventually.

1529
01:45:17,859 --> 01:45:20,135
Everybody who's ever done
any hitchhiking

1530
01:45:20,262 --> 01:45:23,940
knows that basically we can't lose.
When you sit out and hitchhike,

1531
01:45:24,066 --> 01:45:25,944
in the front seat are the parents

1532
01:45:26,068 --> 01:45:30,668
and they give you this real scared,
contemptuous look as they drive by,

1533
01:45:30,793 --> 01:45:35,154
but then, in the back seat, as they
drive away, you see the kids going...

1534
01:45:36,199 --> 01:45:39,672
We got the kids on our side
and we can't lose. We just can't lose.

1535
01:45:39,803 --> 01:45:42,683
When you're in a mass movement
to change society,

1536
01:45:42,806 --> 01:45:48,090
when you're in this experience
of this democracy breaking out,

1537
01:45:48,212 --> 01:45:52,493
you don't want it to end.
You want the storm to continue.

1538
01:45:52,616 --> 01:45:58,298
You want to keep that sense of change
and overwhelming power

1539
01:45:58,423 --> 01:46:00,141
that one gets from the ocean.

1540
01:46:00,265 --> 01:46:03,738
You might not be able
to keep the rowboat straight or up,

1541
01:46:03,869 --> 01:46:07,227
but you don't want the storm to die.

1542
01:46:07,352 --> 01:46:10,825
There was no vision,
no articulate philosophy,

1543
01:46:10,957 --> 01:46:14,235
no conception of social organisation
and social change.

1544
01:46:14,361 --> 01:46:18,243
What there were
were a series of emotional moments,

1545
01:46:18,364 --> 01:46:22,042
a series of passions, a series
of desperately important issues.

1546
01:46:22,169 --> 01:46:24,559
But you can't beat something
with nothing,

1547
01:46:24,691 --> 01:46:28,164
and if you're going to fight
this kind of long cultural battle,

1548
01:46:28,296 --> 01:46:29,695
you are bound to lose

1549
01:46:29,817 --> 01:46:33,608
if you don't have a coherent,
articulate, well-worked-out vision

1550
01:46:33,741 --> 01:46:36,576
of what you're trying to do
and that they didn't have.

1551
01:46:36,704 --> 01:46:39,584
We had taken what we had
as far as we could go.

1552
01:46:39,708 --> 01:46:41,745
I think that it's important

1553
01:46:41,870 --> 01:46:44,944
not to lose sight
of what that movement accomplished.

1554
01:46:45,073 --> 01:46:49,354
That is, it was part of the struggle
for civil rights.

1555
01:46:49,478 --> 01:46:52,119
It was part of the movement
in this country

1556
01:46:52,241 --> 01:46:54,312
that broke down
the Jim Crow barriers

1557
01:46:54,444 --> 01:46:58,076
and changed the caste relationships

1558
01:46:58,207 --> 01:47:01,360
of blacks and other minorities
in our society.

1559
01:47:01,491 --> 01:47:07,766
It was part of the movement
that liberalised American culture.

1560
01:47:07,899 --> 01:47:10,095
It was part of the movement
that gave way

1561
01:47:10,220 --> 01:47:13,498
to the ideas of women's equality
and women's liberation.

1562
01:47:13,624 --> 01:47:16,459
It was part of a movement

1563
01:47:16,588 --> 01:47:20,425
that ultimately made it impossible

1564
01:47:20,552 --> 01:47:24,628
to carry out so blatantly the kind
of imperialistic foreign policy

1565
01:47:24,756 --> 01:47:29,276
that characterised
the period after World War Two.

1566
01:47:29,401 --> 01:47:34,160
American society was profoundly
changed by the movements of the '60s.

1567
01:47:34,287 --> 01:47:40,448
In the '60s, we came
at a certain point in the Cold War

1568
01:47:40,573 --> 01:47:43,647
to reject the ideologies
of both sides,

1569
01:47:43,777 --> 01:47:48,411
and our declaration of freedom
was a political freedom,

1570
01:47:48,543 --> 01:47:50,739
but it had a larger dimension,

1571
01:47:50,864 --> 01:47:53,858
that is, the freedom of imagination.

1572
01:47:56,150 --> 01:47:59,030
Having gained the freedom
to see the world freshly

1573
01:47:59,154 --> 01:48:01,430
and the ability to act for change,

1574
01:48:01,557 --> 01:48:04,835
we carried what we'd learned
into the rest of our lives.

1575
01:48:04,960 --> 01:48:08,034
From personal issues
to planetary concerns,

1576
01:48:08,163 --> 01:48:11,316
we continued to explore
the potential for change.

1577
01:48:11,447 --> 01:48:16,161
And as we watch activists for human
rights and democracy around the world

1578
01:48:16,292 --> 01:48:18,443
challenge the powers that be,

1579
01:48:18,574 --> 01:48:22,650
we know that each generation
has its chance to make things change,

1580
01:48:22,779 --> 01:48:26,137
and that no generation
can do it alone.

1581
01:48:42,001 --> 01:48:43,913
We shall live in peace!

1582
